{"title_page": "Church of the Good Shepherd (Beverly Hills, California)", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2018}}\n{{Infobox church\n| name                 = Church of the Good Shepherd\n| fullname             =\n| image                = Good Shepherd Catholic Church, Beverly Hills.JPG\n| imagesize            =\n| landscape            =\n| caption              = \n| location             = 504 North Roxbury Drive, [[Beverly Hills, California]]\n| country              = United States\n| coordinates          =\n| denomination         = [[Catholic]]\n| tradition            =\n| membership           =\n| attendance           =\n| website              = {{URL|gsbh.org}}\n| former name          =\n| bull date            =\n| founded date         = December 12, 1923 <ref>https://www.gsbh.org/history Our History</ref>\n| founder              =\n| dedication           =\n| dedicated date       = February 1, 1925\n| consecrated date     =\n| cult                 =\n| relics               = [[Felicitas and Perpetua]]<br>[[Saint Vibiana]]\n| events               =\n| past bishop          =\n| people               =\n| status               =\n| functional status    =\n| heritage designation =\n| designated date      =\n| architect            = James J. Donnellan\n| architectural type   = [[Mission Revival Style architecture]]\n| style                =\n| groundbreaking       =\n| completed date       =\n| construction cost    =\n| closed date          =\n| demolished date      =\n| parish               =\n| deanery              =\n| archdeaconry         =\n| diocese              = [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Los Angeles|Archdiocese of Los Angeles]]\n| province             =\n| presbytery           =\n| synod                =\n| circuit              =\n| district             =\n| division             = [[Our Lady of the Angels Pastoral Region]]\n| subdivision          =\n| archbishop           = [[Jos\u00e9 Horacio G\u00f3mez]]\n| bishop               = [[Edward William Clark|Edward W. Clark]]\n| dean                 =\n| subdean              =\n| provost              =\n| provost-rector       =\n| viceprovost          =\n| canon                =\n| canonpastor          =\n| precentor            =\n| archdeacon           =\n| prebendary           =\n| rector               =\n| vicar                =\n| curate               =\n| priest               = \n| pastor               = Fr. Ed Benioff\n| asstpriest           =\n| minister             =\n| assistant            = Fr. George O'Brien (deceased)\n| honpriest            = Fr. Colm O'Ryan\n| deacon               = \n| deaconness           =\n| seniorpastor         =\n| abbot                =\n| chaplain             =\n| reader               =\n| organistdom          =\n| director             =\n| organist             = Mr. Terry Hicks\n| organscholar         =\n| chapterclerk         =\n| laychapter           =\n| warden               =\n| flowerguild          =\n| musicgroup           =\n| parishadmin          =\n| serversguild         =\n| logo                 =\n| logosize             =\n}}\nThe '''Church of the Good Shepherd''', located at 504 North Roxbury Drive, is a [[Catholic Church|Catholic]] church in [[Beverly Hills, California]].\n\n==History==\nOn December 12, 1923, the parish was founded, and it was designed by architect [[James J. Donnellan]] in 1924.<ref name=\"history\">[http://www.goodshepherdbh.org/a-city-on-a-hill/our-history/ Official website, History]</ref><ref name=\"owen\">Thomas Owen, [http://www.sacredarchitecture.org/articles/los_angeles_and_the_mission_revival/ Los Angeles and the Mission Revival], ''[[Sacred Architecture (journal)|Sacred Architecture]]'', Vol. 2, Summer 1999</ref><ref name=\"earlybh\">Marc Wanamaker, ''Early Beverly Hills'', Arcadia Publishing, 2005, p. 118 [https://books.google.com/books?id=gwMyg0wEdDEC&pg=PA118]</ref> It is [[Mission Revival Style architecture]].<ref name=\"owen\"/> On February 1, 1925, Bishop [[John Joseph Cantwell]] presided over the dedication of the church building.<ref name=\"history\"/> It is the oldest church in Beverly Hills.<ref name=\"yahoolocal\">[http://local.yahoo.com/info-20450039-good-shepherd-catholic-church-beverly-hills Yahoo! Local]</ref>\n\nIn 1959, it was renovated, and a new marble main altar and two side altars were added.<ref name=\"history\"/><ref name=\"earlybh\"/> Sealed in each altar were the relics of Saints [[Felicitas and Perpetua]] and [[Saint Vibiana]], patroness of the Los Angeles Archdiocese.<ref name=\"history\"/>\n\nOn [[Ash Wednesday]] in 2015, the deacon from Good Shepherd offered ashes to passers-by on the streets of Beverly Hills together with the deacon of [[All Saints' Episcopal Church (Beverly Hills, California)|All Saints' Episcopal Church]].<ref>Nita Lelyveld, [http://www.latimes.com/local/westside/la-me-beat-street-ashes-20150219-story.html On Ash Wednesday, two deacons deliver on the streets of Beverly Hills], ''The Los Angeles Times'', February 18, 2015</ref>\n\n==Stained glass==\nThe original stained glass was shipped from [[France]], [[Germany]], the [[British Isles]] and the U.S.<ref name=\"stainedglass\">'A Guide to the Stained Glass', leaflet, Church of the Good Shepherd, Beverly Hills, CA</ref> It was renovated by the Paul Phillips Studio in 1959.<ref name=\"stainedglass\"/> It depicts the following saints:\n*(along the [[nave]], from the rear to the [[altar]] on the right): [[John the Evangelist]], [[Saint Patrick]], [[Saint Joseph]], [[Paul the Apostle]], [[Madonna (art)|Madonna]] and Child, and [[Good Shepherd]].<ref name=\"stainedglass\"/>\n*(along the nave, from the rear to the altar on the left): the [[Sacred Heart]] of Jesus, [[Saint Peter]], [[Michael (archangel)|St Michael the Archangel]], Saint [[Anthony of Padua]], and [[Saint Anne]] with the [[Mary (mother of Jesus)|Young Blessed Virgin]].<ref name=\"stainedglass\"/>\n*(in the [[Confession (religion)|Reconciliation]] rooms): Saint [[Agnes of Rome|Agnes]] and [[Saint Cecilia]].<ref name=\"stainedglass\"/>\n*(in the [[Vestibule (architecture)|vestibule]]): three small windows showing the heads of [[cherub]]s bordered by roses.<ref name=\"stainedglass\"/>\n*(in the [[sacristy]] workrooms): one window shows wheat stalks and host; another window shows grapes and grapevines surrounding a [[chalice]].<ref name=\"stainedglass\"/>\n*(in the vesting room): one window on the left shows a [[thurible]] framed by a priest's [[Stole (vestment)|stole]]; the window next to it shows a [[lectionary]] with a bookmark and the words \"Leccio Sti. Petri Apostli.\"; the window on the right shows a chalice, candles and a cross.<ref name=\"stainedglass\"/>\n\n==Parishioners==\nOver the years, this small house of worship has been the local parish church for most of the Catholic movie stars who live in Beverly Hills, from [[Rudolph Valentino]] to [[Bing Crosby]] (who both attended Sunday Mass here).<ref name=\"yahoolocal\"/> It has seen numerous celebrity weddings and funerals. Celebrity weddings have included [[Elizabeth Taylor]] and [[Conrad Hilton, Jr.|Conrad \"Nicky\" Hilton]], [[Loretta Young]] and Tom Lewis, [[Mark Wahlberg]] and [[Rhea Durham]], and [[Carmen Miranda]] and David Sebastian.<ref name=\"yahoolocal\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1913&dat=19470317&id=a3xhAAAAIBAJ&sjid=5GYFAAAAIBAJ&pg=4682,5996739&hl=pt-BR|title=Carmen Miranda Honeymooning With David Sebastian|author=|date=March 17, 1947|publisher=Lewiston Evening Journal |accessdate=June 30, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"bhwanamaker\">Marc Wanamaker, ''Beverly Hills, 1930-2005'', Arcadia Publishing, 2006, p. 83 [https://books.google.com/books?id=CRZ1dl-p_-4C&pg=PA83&dq=%22church+of+the+good+shepherd%22+%22beverly+hills%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=gX1XUsPyIoXL0QWrg4GgBQ&ved=0CDMQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=%22church%20of%20the%20good%20shepherd%22%20%22beverly%20hills%22&f=false]</ref> Celebrity funerals have included [[Rudolph Valentino]] (1926), [[Carmen Miranda]] (1955), [[Gary Cooper]] (1961), [[William Frawley]] (1966), [[Pier Angeli]] (1971), [[Jack Haley]] (1979), [[Alfred Hitchcock]] (1980), [[Vincente Minnelli]] (1986), [[Rita Hayworth]] (1987), [[Danny Thomas]] (1991), [[Eva Gabor]] (1995), [[Mary Frann]] (1998), [[Frank Sinatra]] (1998), [[Don Adams]] (2005), [[Merv Griffin]] (2007) and [[Zsa Zsa Gabor]] (2016).<ref name=\"earlybh\"/><ref name=\"yahoolocal\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbclosangeles.com/news/local/Zsa-Zsa-Gabors-Funeral-Set-For-Next-Week-408061005.html|title=Zsa Zsa Gabor's Funeral Set For Next Week|publisher=[[NBC News]].com|accessdate=December 30, 2016|date=December 20, 2016}}</ref>\n\nA [[Rosary]] was said at the church for the singer and actress [[Rosemary Clooney]]. In attendance were [[George Clooney]], [[Kathryn Crosby]], [[Frank Sinatra, Jr.]], [[Brian Wilson]], [[Natalie Cole]], [[Diahann Carroll]], and [[Rose Marie]]. Her actual funeral service was held at St. Patrick's, in her hometown of [[Maysville, Kentucky]]. Actor Gary Cooper had converted to Catholicism at this parish a few years before his death. His funeral service was held at the church on the same day as the [[13th Primetime Emmy Awards]].\n\nIt was the location for the funeral scene in the film ''[[A Star Is Born (1954 film)|A Star Is Born]]'' (1954), which starred [[Judy Garland]] and [[James Mason]].\n{{commons category|Church of the Good Shepherd (Beverly Hills, California)}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Los Angeles|state=collapsed}}\n{{coord|34|4|10|N|118|24|27|W|type:landmark|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Roman Catholic churches in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic churches in California]]\n[[Category:Mission Revival architecture in California]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic churches completed in 1925]]\n[[Category:Religious buildings and structures in Beverly Hills, California]]\n[[Category:Churches in Los Angeles County, California]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2018}}\n