y Party politicians]]\n[[Category:Candidates for President of Brazil]]\n[[Category:Governors of S\u00e3o Paulo (state)]]\n[[Category:Vice Governors of S\u00e3o Paulo (state)]]\n[[Category:Brazilian Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:20th-century Brazilian physicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Portuguese name|Rodrigues|Alckmin}}\n{{Expand Portuguese|Geraldo Alckmin|date=December 2014}}\n{{update|date=April 2015}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name           = Geraldo Alckmin\n|image          = Geraldo Alckmin em agosto de 2017.jpg\n|office         = National President of the [[Brazilian Social Democracy Party]]\n|term_start     = 9 December 2017\n|term_end       = 31 May 2019\n|predecessor    = [[Alberto Goldman]] {{small|(Acting)}}\n|successor      = [[Bruno Ara\u00fajo]]\n|office1        = 31st and 35th [[List of Governors of S\u00e3o Paulo|Governor of S\u00e3o Paulo]]\n|vicegovernor1  = [[Guilherme Afif Domingos]] {{small|(2011\u20132015)}}<br />[[M\u00e1rcio Fran\u00e7a]] {{small|(2015\u20132018)}}\n|term_start1    = 1 January 2011\n|term_end1      = 6 April 2018\n|predecessor1   = [[Alberto Goldman]]\n|successor1     = [[M\u00e1rcio Fran\u00e7a]]\n|vicegovernor2  = ''Vacant'' {{small|(2001\u20132005)}}<br /> [[Cl\u00e1udio Lembo]] {{small|(2005\u20132006)}}\n|term_start2    = 6 March 2001\n|term_end2      = 30 March 2006<br />{{small|Acting: 22 January 2001 \u2013 6 March 2001}}\n|predecessor2   = [[M\u00e1rio Covas]] \n|successor2     = [[Cl\u00e1udio Lembo]]\n|office3        = Secretary of Development of S\u00e3o Paulo\n|term_start3    = 19 January 2009\n|term_end3      = 1 April 2010\n|governor3      = [[Jos\u00e9 Serra]]\n|predecessor3   = [[Alberto Goldman]]\n|successor3     = [[Luciano Almeida]]\n|office4        = Vice Governor of S\u00e3o Paulo\n|term_start4    = 1 January 1995\n|term_end4      = 6 March 2001\n|governor4      = [[M\u00e1rio Covas]]\n|predecessor4   = [[Aloysio Nunes]]\n|successor4     = [[Cl\u00e1udio Lembo]]\n|office5        = [[Chamber of Deputies (Brazil)|Federal Deputy]] for [[S\u00e3o Paulo (state)|S\u00e3o Paulo]]\n|term_start5    = 1 February 1987\n|term_end5      = 15 December 1994\n|office6        = [[Legislative Assembly of S\u00e3o Paulo|State Deputy of S\u00e3o Paulo]]\n|term_start6    = 1 February 1983\n|term_end6      = 1 February 1987\n|office7        = 27th Mayor of [[Pindamonhangaba]]\n|term_start7    = 15 March 1977\n|term_end7      = 15 May 1982\n|predecessor7   = Jo\u00e3o Bosco Nogueira\n|successor7     = Thiers Fernandes Lobo\n|office8        = Alderman of [[Pindamonhangaba]]\n|term_start8    = 1 February 1973\n|term_end8      = 1 February 1977\n|birth_name     = Geraldo Jos\u00e9 Rodrigues de Alckmin Filho\n|birth_date     = {{Birth date and age|1952|11|7|df=y}}\n|birth_place    = [[Pindamonhangaba]], [[S\u00e3o Paulo (state)|S\u00e3o Paulo]], [[Brazil]]\n|death_date     = \n|death_place    = \n|party          = [[Brazilian Democratic Movement|PMDB]] {{small|(1972\u20131988)}}<br />[[Brazilian Social Democracy Party|PSDB]] {{small|(1988\u2013present)}}\n|spouse         = {{marriage|[[Maria L\u00facia Ribeiro Alckmin|Maria L\u00facia Ribeiro]]|1979}}\n|children       = Sophia Alckmin {{small|(b. 1981)}} <br /> Geraldo Alckmin Neto {{small|(b. 1982)}} <br /> Thomaz Alckmin {{small|(1983 \u2013 2015)}}\n|alma_mater     = [[University of Taubat\u00e9]]\n|signature      = Geraldo Alckmin assinatura de governador de SP.jpg\n|website        = [https://web.archive.org/web/20101006092539/http://www.geraldo45.org.br/ Official website]\n}}\n'''Geraldo Jos\u00e9 Rodrigues de Alckmin Filho''' ({{IPA-pt|\u0292e\u02c8\u027eawdu \u02c8a\u026bkm\u0129}}; born 7 November 1952) is a [[Brazilian people|Brazilian]] politician who served as the [[Governor of S\u00e3o Paulo]] from 2001 to 2006, and then again from 2011 to 2018. He was the [[Brazilian Social Democracy Party]] (PSDB) presidential nominee for the [[2018 Brazilian general election|2018 presidential election]]. He is usually described by political analysts and supporters as a pro-business centrist, closely associated with the political and financial establishment.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-05-15/brazil-s-pro-business-candidate-won-t-win-alone-protege-says|title=Brazil's Pro-Business Candidate Won't Win Alone, Protege Says|date=2018-05-15|work=Bloomberg.com|access-date=2018-05-25|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAlckmin was elected governor of S\u00e3o Paulo in 2010 and reelected in [[2014 S\u00e3o Paulo gubernatorial election|2014]], for the fourth (not consecutive) time.<ref>[http://agenciabrasil.ebc.com.br/en/politica/noticia/2014-10/alckmin-elected-sao-paulo-governor-4th-time Alckmin elected S\u00e3o Paulo governor for 4th time] Ag\u00eancia Brasil, October 5, 2014</ref> He was previously his party's candidate for [[president of Brazil]] in the [[2006 Brazilian general elections|2006 elections]]. He attended the [[Universidade de Taubat\u00e9]]'s medical school, specializing in [[Anesthesiology]], before going on to work in the S\u00e3o Paulo Public Service Hospital. He resigned on 6 April 2018 to run for president, for a second time, in the 2018 elections.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://noticias.r7.com/brasil/governador-com-mais-tempo-no-cargo-alckmin-renuncia-nesta-sexta-06042018|title=Governador com mais tempo no cargo, Alckmin renuncia nesta sexta|website=Noticias.r7.com|language=pt|first=Fernando|last=Mellis|trans-title=Governor with longest time in office, Alckmin resigns this Friday|date=6 April 2018|accessdate=6 April 2018}}</ref> His vice governor [[M\u00e1rcio Fran\u00e7a]] will hold the office until the end of the term.\n\n==Biography==\nGeraldo Jos\u00e9 Rodriguez Alckmin Filho was born in the city of [[Pindamonhangaba]], [[Vale do Para\u00edba]]. Alckmin is the son of Geraldo Jos\u00e9 Rodriguez Alckmin and Miriam Penteado. Geraldo is the nephew of Jos\u00e9 Geraldo Rodriguez de Alckmin, who was a minister of the Supreme Federal Court. According to \u00c9poca magazine, Geraldo received a Christian formation from the [[Opus Dei]] Catholic prelature, and told the magazine that his uncle Jose Geraldo was from Opus Dei.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://revistaepoca.globo.com/Epoca/0,6993,EPT1107598-1664,00.html |title=O Governador e a Obra |publisher=[[\u00c9poca (revista)|\u00c9poca]] |author=Eliane Brum e Ricardo Mendon\u00e7a |date=16 January 2006 |accessdate=May 12, 2017}}</ref>\n\nGeraldo is married to Maria L\u00facia Ribeiro Alckmin and is the father of three children. Sophia, Geraldo and Thomaz.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www1.folha.uol.com.br/folha/especial/2006/eleicoes/candidatos-presidente-geraldo_alckmin.shtml |title= Candidatos - Presidente - Geraldo Alckmin |publisher=[[Folha de S.Paulo]] |date=12 August 2006 |accessdate= 30 April 2016|language= pt}}</ref> Thomaz died in a helicopter accident on 2 April 2015.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-3024235/Five-killed-helicopter-flown-son-governor-Geraldo-Alckmin-crashes-Sao-Paulo-house.html |title= Helicopter crashes into Sao Paulo house killing five including local politician\u2019s son |publisher=[[Daily Mail]] |author= Tim MacFarlan|date=6 April 2015 |accessdate= 30 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nWhile still in his first year of medical school, Alckmin began his political career in 1972 when he was elected to the [[Pindamonhangaba]] city council (1973\u20131977), and then its mayor (1977\u20131982). At age 25, he was the youngest Brazilian mayor. He was elected a federal deputy for two terms, (1983\u20131987 and 1987\u20131994), distinguishing himself by authoring consumer protection laws. In 1988, he was one of the founders of the [[Brazilian Social Democracy Party]] (PSDB).\n\nHe was elected vice [[governor of S\u00e3o Paulo]], [[M\u00e1rio Covas]]'s running-mate first in the 1994 election and then again in 1998. With the death of Covas, he assumed the governorship of the state of S\u00e3o Paulo in March, 2001, he continued Covas' policies, investing in large, state-run projects, health and education programs. All of these investments were possible through   [[privatization]] programs that sold off public and state-owned companies. He was elected governor on October 27, 2002, through a [[runoff election]], for the 2003-2006 term, with 12 million votes (or 58.64%). His current administration is marked by a reduction in the state payroll from 49% to 46% of the state's budget, the unification of purchasing systems and other \"smart spending\" initiatives, as well as the implementation of [[Public-Private Partnership]]s (PPPs).\n\n==2006 presidential election==\nOn March 14, 2006, [[Brazilian Social Democracy Party|PSDB]] nominated Alckmin as its candidate for President in the [[2006 Brazilian general election|2006 elections]]. Because of electoral rules, no candidate running for office may currently be in an executive office, forcing him to resign the governorship on March 31, 2006. [[Cl\u00e1udio Lembo]], the [[lieutenant governor]], finished Alckmin's term. Alckmin's party mate, [[Jos\u00e9 Serra]], the PSDB's presidential standard-bearer who lost to Luiz In\u00e1cio Lula da Silva in 2002, then announced his candidacy to replace Alckmin in the 2006 state elections. Serra won the vote in Brazil's first round elections on October 1, 2006 and was elected as the governor of S\u00e3o Paulo.\n\nContrary to all major polls taken in the run-up to the October 1, 2006 balloting, Alckmin surprised almost everyone and came in second place in the presidential election{{Citation needed|date=January 2010}}. His 41.64% of the vote,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.justicaeleitoral.gov.br/resultado/index.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2006-10-03 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061201000104/http://www.justicaeleitoral.gov.br/resultado/index.html |archivedate=2006-12-01 }}</ref> along with votes cast for two less significant candidates, as well as ballots that were left blank or spoiled, was enough to deny the [[majority|simple majority]] necessary to re-elect incumbent President [[Luiz In\u00e1cio Lula da Silva]] (\"Lula\") in the first round. Lula and Alckmin faced one another in a run-off election on October 29, 2006. Alckmin received 39% of the vote, losing to Lula, who received 61% of the vote and was then reelected.\n\n==Return to S\u00e3o Paulo==\nOn January 19, 2009, Geraldo was appointed Secretary of Development for the State of S\u00e3o Paulo by then-Governor [[Jos\u00e9 Serra]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www1.folha.uol.com.br/folha/brasil/ult96u491863.shtml |title=Alckmin \u00e9 o novo secret\u00e1rio de Desenvolvimento de Serra |publisher=[[Folha de S.Paulo]] |author=Jos\u00e9 Alberto Bombig e Fernando Barros de Mello |date=19 January 2009 |access-date=18 August 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.clicrbs.com.br/anoticia/jsp/default.jsp?uf=2&local=18&section=Pol%C3%ADtica&newsID=a2374147.xml |title=Geraldo Alckmin assume secretaria em S\u00e3o Paulo |publisher=Clicrbs |date=19 January 2009 |access-date=18 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Governor of S\u00e3o Paulo; 2011\u20132018==\n===State Elections 2010===\nAt the PSDB Convenction held on June 13, 2010, Alckmin was officially named the party's candidate for the S\u00e3o Paulo government.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www1.folha.uol.com.br/poder/750178-psdb-lanca-candidatura-de-geraldo-alckmin-ao-governo-paulista.shtml |title=PSDB lan\u00e7a Geraldo Alckmin candidato ao governo paulista |publisher=[[Folha de S.Paulo]] |author=Daniel Roncaglia |date=June 13, 2010 |accessdate=May 12, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAlckmin was elected governor in the first round with 11.5 million votes (50.63%) defeating Senator Aloizio Mercadante (PT) who obtained 8 million votes (35.23%).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://eleicoes.folha.uol.com.br/2010/1turno/apuracao-governador.shtml |title=Apura\u00e7\u00e3o completa - Governador |publisher=[[Folha de S.Paulo]] |date=October 3, 2010 |accessdate=May 12, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Third term as Governor; 2011\u20132014===\nAlckmin assumed the government of S\u00e3o Paulo for the third time on January 1, 2011. The inauguration took place during a ceremony held at State Legislative Assembly.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www1.folha.uol.com.br/poder/853481-alckmin-toma-posse-e-promete-trabalhar-nao-apenas-por-sao-paulo-mas-pelo-brasil.shtml |title=Alckmin toma posse e promete trabalhar 'n\u00e3o apenas por S\u00e3o Paulo, mas pelo Brasil' |publisher=[[Folha de S.Paulo]] |date=1 January 2011 |accessdate=17 August 2013}}</ref>\n\nHis administration in 2013 faces strikes in education and health.<ref name=\"Sa\u00fade\">{{cite web|url=http://www.estadao.com.br/noticias/vidae,greve-afeta-14-hospitais-estaduais-na-capital-diz-sindicato,1039094,0.htm|title=Greve afeta 14 hospitais estaduais na capital, diz sindicato|author=Gabriela Vieira e Ricardo Chapola |date=5 June 2013 |work=[[O Estado de S. Paulo]] |access-date=4 July 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Educa\u00e7\u00e3o\">{{cite web|url=http://g1.globo.com/sao-paulo/noticia/2013/04/professores-decidem-greve-em-assembleia-na-avenida-paulista.html|title=Professores decidem greve em assembleia na Avenida Paulista|last=Viana|first=Julia Basso|date=19 April 2013|work=Portal G1|language=pt|access-date=4 July 2013}}</ref> After the readjustment in the passage of the metropolitan trains and the subway, great manifestations of protests began, that also happened in all Brazil. The readjustment was later suspended by Alckmin and the mayor of S\u00e3o Paulo, Fernando Haddad.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://noticias.terra.com.br/brasil/cidades/haddad-e-alckmin-anunciam-reducao-das-tarifas-para-r-3-em-sp,fc2b18f9d2e5f310VgnVCM5000009ccceb0aRCRD.html |title=Haddad e Alckmin anunciam redu\u00e7\u00e3o das tarifas para R$ 3 em SP |date=19 June 2013 |accessdate=May 12, 2017 |work=[[Terra (portal)|Terra]]}}</ref>\n\nAlckmin's reelection campaign for 2014 was officialized on June 29, 2014.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://g1.globo.com/sao-paulo/eleicoes/2014/noticia/2014/06/psdb-oficializa-reeleicao-de-geraldo-alckmin-ao-governo-paulista.html |title=PSDB oficializa candidatura de Alckmin \u00e0 reelei\u00e7\u00e3o ao governo de SP |publisher=[[G1 (website)|G1]] |author=Tatiana Santiago |date=29 June 2014 |accessdate=May 12, 2017}}</ref> In the first round, on October 5, 2014, he was re-elected with 12.2 million votes (57.31%), being the second highest percentage of votes since the redemocratization of Brazil.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://politica.estadao.com.br/noticias/eleicoes,geraldo-alckmin-e-reeleito-governador-de-sp-com-57-dos-votos,1571763 |title=Geraldo Alckmin \u00e9 reeleito governador de SP com 57% dos votos |publisher=[[O Estado de S. Paulo]] |author=Paulo Salda\u00f1a |date=5 October 2014 |accessdate=May 12, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Fourth Term; 2015\u20132018===\nGeraldo Alckmin took office for the fourth time as governor of S\u00e3o Paulo on January 1, 2015.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://noticias.terra.com.br/brasil/politica/alckmin-assume-4-mandato-e-nao-cita-crise-hidrica-em-sp,38d82c6b7d5aa410VgnVCM4000009bcceb0aRCRD.html |title=Alckmin assume 4\u00ba mandato e n\u00e3o cita crise h\u00eddrica em SP |publisher=[[Terra (portal)|Terra]] |author=D\u00e9bora Melo e Janaina Garcia |date=1 January 2015 |accessdate=May 12, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==2018 presidential campaign==\n{{main|Geraldo Alckmin presidential campaign, 2018}}\nIn a convention held on 9 December 2017, Alckmin was elected the PSDB's national president in a 470-3 vote, succeeding [[Minas Gerais]] senator [[A\u00e9cio Neves]], and announced his pre-candidacy for next year's presidential race.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://g1.globo.com/politica/noticia/psdb-elege-geraldo-alckmin-como-presidente-nacional-do-partido.ghtml|title=Por 470 votos a 3, PSDB elege Geraldo Alckmin presidente nacional do partido|website=G1.globo.com|accessdate=1 November 2018}}</ref> On 23 February 2018, after [[Manaus]] mayor [[Arthur Virg\u00edlio Neto]] suspended his campaign, Alckmin became the sole candidate for the party's [[primary election|primary]]. His candidacy became official on 6 March 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www1.folha.uol.com.br/poder/2018/02/nao-vou-participar-dessa-fraude-diz-arthur-virgilio-sobre-previas-com-alckmin.shtml|title=Arthur Virg\u00edlio\u00a0desiste, e Alckmin\u00a0deve ser candidato do PSDB \u00e0 Presid\u00eancia|date=23 February 2018|website=1.folha.uol.com.br|accessdate=1 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nSince resigning as governor and losing his [[legal immunity]], Alckmin has been the target of a probe by electoral justice authorities for allegations that construction company [[Odebrecht]] illegally funneled R$10 million into his 2010 and 2014 campaign. He has denied wrongdoing, saying the funds were of \"electoral nature\" and that the allegation \"does not proceed\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://politica.estadao.com.br/noticias/geral,alckmin-diz-que-delacao-da-odebrecht-e-de-natureza-eleitoral-e-nao-tem-procedencia,70002264330|title=Alckmin diz que dela\u00e7\u00e3o da Odebrecht \u00e9 de 'natureza eleitoral' e 'n\u00e3o tem proced\u00eancia' - Pol\u00edtica - Estad\u00e3o|website=Politica.estadao.com.br|accessdate=1 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn early May 2018, Alckmin announced his campaign communications team, which is headed by Luis Felipe d'Avila with Lula Guimar\u00e3es as marketing director.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://blogs.oglobo.globo.com/lauro-jardim/post/o-time-da-comunicacao.html|title=O time da comunica\u00e7\u00e3o - Lauro Jardim - O Globo|first=Lauro|last=Jardim|website=Lauro Jardim - O Globo|accessdate=1 November 2018}}</ref> Later that month, he announced his economic advisorial team, which includes [[Plano Real]] economists [[Edmar Bacha]] and [[Persio Arida]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://politica.estadao.com.br/noticias/geral,alckmin-anuncia-equipe-economica-com-criadores-do-plano-real,70002312544|title=Alckmin anuncia equipe econ\u00f4mica com criadores do Plano Real - Pol\u00edtica - Estad\u00e3o|website=Politica.estadao.com.br|accessdate=1 November 2018}}</ref> In late July, Alckmin negotiated a coalition with the ''\"centr\u00e3o\"'' (big centre), a group of parties in Congress composed of [[Democrats (Brazil)|DEM]], [[Progressistas|PP]], [[Party of the Republic|PR]], [[Brazilian Republican Party|PRB]] and [[Solidariedade|SD]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://g1.globo.com/politica/blog/valdo-cruz/post/2018/07/26/apos-ameacas-de-divisao-centrao-fecha-com-alckmin-para-tentar-chegar-ao-segundo-turno.ghtml|title=Ap\u00f3s amea\u00e7as de divis\u00e3o, Centr\u00e3o fecha com Alckmin para tentar chegar ao segundo turno|website=G1.globo.com|accessdate=1 November 2018}}</ref> On 2 August 2018, [[Rio Grande do Sul]] senator [[Ana Am\u00e9lia Lemos]], a member of PP, was confirmed as Alckmin's running mate in the general election.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.poder360.com.br/eleicoes/alckmin-confirma-ana-amelia-como-vice/|title=Alckmin confirma Ana Am\u00e9lia como vice|date=2 August 2018|website=Poder360.com.br|accessdate=1 November 2018}}</ref> As the candidate with the largest coalition, Alckmin has secured the longest slot for [[party political broadcast|political ads]] on [[free-to-air]] television channels.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www1.folha.uol.com.br/poder/2018/08/alckmin-tera-44-da-tv-lideres-bolsonaro-e-marina-dependerao-da-internet.shtml|title=Alckmin ter\u00e1 44% da TV; l\u00edderes, Bolsonaro e Marina depender\u00e3o da internet|date=5 August 2018|website=1.folha.uol.com.br|accessdate=1 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nAs candidate, Alckmin has proposed a smaller government and reduction of taxes, and has defended the labor reform that took place in the administration of President [[Michel Temer]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nexojornal.com.br/expresso/2018/08/10/A-trajet%C3%B3ria-de-Alckmin-candidato-do-PSDB-%C3%A0-Presid%C3%AAncia|title=A trajet\u00f3ria de Alckmin, candidato do PSDB \u00e0 Presid\u00eancia|website=Nexojornal.com.br|accessdate=1 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Geraldo Alckmin}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060715182738/http://www.geraldo45.com/ Geraldo 45 - unofficial website]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Aloysio Nunes]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Vice Governor of [[S\u00e3o Paulo (state)|S\u00e3o Paulo]]|years=1995\u20132001}}\n{{s-vac|next=[[Cl\u00e1udio Lembo]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[M\u00e1rio Covas]]}}\n{{s-ttl|rows=2|title=[[List of Governors of S\u00e3o Paulo|Governor of S\u00e3o Paulo]]|years=2001\u20132006; 2011\u20132018}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Cl\u00e1udio Lembo]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Alberto Goldman]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[M\u00e1rcio Fran\u00e7a]]}}\n|-\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[M\u00e1rio Covas]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Brazilian Social Democracy Party|PSDB]] nominee for [[List of Governors of S\u00e3o Paulo|Governor of S\u00e3o Paulo]]|years=2002, [[2010 S\u00e3o Paulo gubernatorial election|2010]], [[2014 S\u00e3o Paulo gubernatorial election|2014]]|rows=2}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Jos\u00e9 Serra]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Jos\u00e9 Serra]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Jo\u00e3o Doria]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Jos\u00e9 Serra]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Brazilian Social Democracy Party|PSDB]] nominee for [[List of Mayors of S\u00e3o Paulo|Mayor of S\u00e3o Paulo]]|years=[[2008 S\u00e3o Paulo mayoral election|2008]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Jos\u00e9 Serra]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Jos\u00e9 Serra]]}}\n{{s-ttl|rows=2|title=[[Brazilian Social Democracy Party|PSDB]] nominee for [[President of Brazil]]|years=[[2006 Brazilian general election|2006]], [[2018 Brazilian general election|2018]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Jos\u00e9 Serra]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[A\u00e9cio Neves]]}}\n{{s-inc|recent}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Alberto Goldman]]<br>{{small|Acting}}}}\n{{s-ttl|title=President of the [[Brazilian Social Democracy Party]]|years=2017\u20132019}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Bruno Ara\u00fajo]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{S\u00e3oPauloGovernors}}\n{{BrazilGovernors}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Alckmin, Geraldo}}\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Pindamonhangaba]]\n[[Category:Brazilian anesthesiologists]]\n[[Category:Brazilian Social Democracy Party politicians]]\n[[Category:Candidates for President of Brazil]]\n[[Category:Governors of S\u00e3o Paulo (state)]]\n[[Category:Vice Governors of S\u00e3o Paulo (state)]]\n[[Category:Brazilian Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:20th-century Brazilian physicians]]\n", "name_user": "Chris the speller", "label": "safe", "comment": "replaced: President \u2192 president,typo(s) fixed: 2003-2006 \u2192 2003\u20132006 (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geraldo_Alckmin"}
{"title_page": "F1 2020 (video game)", "text_new": "{{short description|2020 video game}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{Infobox video game\n| title = F1 2020\n| image = \n| caption = \n| developer = [[Codemasters|Codemasters Birmingham]]\n| publisher = [[Codemasters]]\n| series = ''[[Formula One video games|Formula 1]]''\n| engine =\n| platforms = [[Microsoft Windows]], [[PlayStation 4]], [[Xbox One]], [[Google Stadia|Stadia]]\n| released = 10 July 2020\n| genre = [[Racing video game|Racing]]\n| director = \n| composer = \n| modes = [[Single-player]], [[multiplayer]]\n}}\n\n'''''F1 2020''''' is the official video game of the [[2020 Formula One World Championship|2020 Formula 1]] and [[2020 FIA Formula 2 Championship|Formula 2 Championships]] developed and published by [[Codemasters]]. It is the thirteenth title in the [[Formula One video games|''Formula 1'' series]] developed by the studio and will be released on 10 July 2020 for [[Microsoft Windows]], [[PlayStation 4]], [[Xbox One]] and [[Google Stadia|Stadia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2020-04-15-this-years-f1-game-lets-you-manage-your-own-team |title=This year's F1 game lets you manage your own team |website=[[Eurogamer]] |first=Martin |last=Robinson |date=April 15, 2020 |accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref> The game is the twelfth installment in the franchise, and it features all twenty-two circuits, twenty drivers and ten teams present in the 2020 Formula 1 World Championship. ''F1 2020'' will feature the championship as it was originally intended to be run; the championship was disrupted by the [[COVID-19 pandemic]], which saw several races cancelled.\n\n==Features==\nThe [[Hanoi Street Circuit]] and [[Zandvoort Circuit]]&mdash;circuits which are new to the championship in 2020&mdash;will be included in the game despite the postponement of the [[Vietnamese Grand Prix|Vietnamese]] and [[Dutch Grand Prix|Dutch Grands Prix]].<ref name=\"my team\"/> ''F1 2020'' will introduce a team management feature known as \"My Team\" which allows the player to create and run an eleventh team.<ref name=\"my team\">{{cite web|url=https://www.autosport.com/f1/news/149029/f1-2020-game-includes-management-mode |title=F1 2020 game to be released in July, includes management mode |website=[[Autosport]] |first=Josh |last=Suttill |date=April 15, 2020 |accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref> Codemasters had previously used the My Team mode in ''[[Dirt 4]]'', a part of the ''[[Colin McRae Rally|Dirt Rally]]'' franchise. The game will also continue the series' trend of including historical Formula 1 cars as [[downloadable content]], and will feature four cars driven by [[Michael Schumacher]].<ref name=\"my team\"/> These include the [[Jordan 191]], [[Benetton B194]], [[Benetton B195]] and the [[Ferrari F1-2000]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://www.codemasters.com/game/f1-2020/}}\n\n{{Formula One games}}\n{{EGO Engine games}}\n\n[[Category:Upcoming video games scheduled for 2020]]\n[[Category:Codemasters games]]\n[[Category:Esports games]]\n[[Category:Formula One video games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation 4 games]]\n[[Category:Racing video games]]\n[[Category:Video games scored by Mark Knight]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Video games set in Australia]]\n[[Category:Video games set in Austria]]\n[[Category:Video games set in Azerbaijan]]\n[[Category:Video games set in Bahrain]]\n[[Category:Video games set in Belgium]]\n[[Category:Video games set in Brazil]]\n[[Category:Video games set in Canada]]\n[[Category:Video games set in China]]\n[[Category:Video games set in France]]\n[[Category:Video games set in Germany]]\n[[Category:Video games set in Hungary]]\n[[Category:Video games set in Italy]]\n[[Category:Video games set in Japan]]\n[[Category:Video games set in Mexico]]\n[[Category:Video games set in Monaco]]\n[[Category:Video games set in Russia]]\n[[Category:Video games set in Singapore]]\n[[Category:Video games set in Spain]]\n[[Category:Video games set in Texas]]\n[[Category:Video games set in the United Arab Emirates]]\n[[Category:Video games set in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Windows games]]\n[[Category:Xbox One games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation 4 Pro enhanced games]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2020 video game}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{Infobox video game\n| title = F1 2020\n| image = \n| caption = \n| developer = [[Codemasters|Codemasters Birmingham]]\n| publisher = [[Codemasters]]\n| series = ''[[Formula One video games|Formula 1]]''\n| engine =\n| platforms = [[Microsoft Windows]], [[PlayStation 4]], [[Xbox One]], [[Google Stadia|Stadia]]\n| released = 10 July 2020\n| genre = [[Racing video game|Racing]]\n| director = \n| composer = \n| modes = [[Single-player]], [[multiplayer]]\n}}\n\n'''''F1 2020''''' is the official video game of the [[2020 Formula One World Championship|2020 Formula 1]] and [[2020 FIA Formula 2 Championship|Formula 2 Championships]] developed and published by [[Codemasters]]. It is the thirteenth title in the [[Formula One video games|''Formula 1'' series]] developed by the studio and will be released on 10 July 2020 for [[Microsoft Windows]], [[PlayStation 4]], [[Xbox One]] and [[Google Stadia|Stadia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2020-04-15-this-years-f1-game-lets-you-manage-your-own-team |title=This year's F1 game lets you manage your own team |website=[[Eurogamer]] |first=Martin |last=Robinson |date=April 15, 2020 |accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref> The game is the twelfth installment in the franchise, and it features all twenty-two circuits, twenty drivers and ten teams present in the 2020 Formula 1 World Championship. ''F1 2020'' will feature the championship as it was originally intended to be run; the championship was disrupted by the [[COVID-19 pandemic]], which saw several races cancelled.\n\n==Features==\nThe [[Hanoi Street Circuit]] and [[Zandvoort Circuit]]&mdash;circuits which are new to the championship in 2020&mdash;will be included in the game despite the postponement of the [[Vietnamese Grand Prix|Vietnamese]] and [[Dutch Grand Prix|Dutch Grands Prix]].<ref name=\"my team\"/> ''F1 2020'' will introduce a team management feature known as \"My Team\" which allows the player to create and run an eleventh team.<ref name=\"my team\">{{cite web|url=https://www.autosport.com/f1/news/149029/f1-2020-game-includes-management-mode |title=F1 2020 game to be released in July, includes management mode |website=[[Autosport]] |first=Josh |last=Suttill |date=April 15, 2020 |accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref> Codemasters had previously used the My Team mode in ''[[Dirt 4]]'', a part of the ''[[Colin McRae Rally|Dirt Rally]]'' franchise. The game will also continue the series' trend of including historical Formula 1 cars as [[downloadable content]], and will feature four cars driven by [[Michael Schumacher]].<ref name=\"my team\"/> These include the [[Jordan 191]], [[Benetton B194]], [[Benetton B195]] and the [[Ferrari F1-2000]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Formula One games}}\n{{EGO Engine games}}\n{{Codemasters}}\n\n[[Category:Upcoming video games scheduled for 2020]]\n[[Category:Codemasters games]]\n[[Category:Esports games]]\n[[Category:Formula One video games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation 4 games]]\n[[Category:Racing video games]]\n[[Category:Video games scored by Mark Knight]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Video games set in Australia]]\n[[Category:Video games set in Austria]]\n[[Category:Video games set in Azerbaijan]]\n[[Category:Video games set in Bahrain]]\n[[Category:Video games set in Belgium]]\n[[Category:Video games set in Brazil]]\n[[Category:Video games set in Canada]]\n[[Category:Video games set in China]]\n[[Category:Video games set in France]]\n[[Category:Video games set in Germany]]\n[[Category:Video games set in Hungary]]\n[[Category:Video games set in Italy]]\n[[Category:Video games set in Japan]]\n[[Category:Video games set in Mexico]]\n[[Category:Video games set in Monaco]]\n[[Category:Video games set in Russia]]\n[[Category:Video games set in Singapore]]\n[[Category:Video games set in Spain]]\n[[Category:Video games set in Texas]]\n[[Category:Video games set in the United Arab Emirates]]\n[[Category:Video games set in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Windows games]]\n[[Category:Xbox One games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation 4 Pro enhanced games]]\n", "name_user": "OceanHok", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:+ EL", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F1_2020_(video_game)"}
{"title_page": "Cassandra Wilson", "text_new": "{{BLP refimprove|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2011}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name               = Cassandra Wilson\n| image              = Cassandra Wilson.jpg\n| caption             =Cassandra Wilson in 2007\n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_name       =\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1955|12|4}}\n| birth_place        =[[Jackson, Mississippi]], U.S.\n| genre               = Jazz\n| occupation        = Singer\n| years_active     =1985\u2013present\n| label                =[[JMT Records|JMT]], [[Blue Note Records|Blue Note]]\n| associated_acts =[[M-Base|M-Base Collective]]\n| website            = {{URL|cassandrawilson.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Cassandra Wilson''' (born December 4, 1955) is an American [[jazz]] singer, songwriter, and producer from [[Jackson, Mississippi]].<ref>{{cite web  | title = Cassandra Wilson on Allmusic.com | url={{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p7837|pure_url=yes}} | accessdate =November 23, 2009 }}</ref> She has been described by critic [[Gary Giddins]]<ref>[[Gary Giddins|Giddins, Gary]]. (2000). ''Visions of Jazz: The First Century''. Oxford University Press, {{ISBN|978-0-19-513241-0}}, p. 643.</ref> as \"a singer blessed with an unmistakable [[timbre]] and [[Attack (music)|attack]] [who has] expanded the playing field\" by incorporating [[blues]], [[country music|country]], and [[folk music]] into her work.\n\n==Early life and career==\nCassandra Wilson is the third and youngest child of [[Herman Fowlkes, Jr.]], a guitarist, bassist, and music teacher;<ref>Litweiler, John. ''[http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/644655/Cassandra-Wilson Cassandra Wilson],'' [[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica Online]]</ref> and Mary McDaniel, an elementary school teacher who earned her PhD in education. Her ancestry includes [[Fon people|Fon]], [[Yoruba people|Yoruba]], [[Irish people|Irish]] and [[Welsh people|Welsh]]. Between her mother\u2019s love for [[Motown]] and her father\u2019s dedication to jazz, Wilson\u2019s parents sparked her early interest in music.<ref name=\"Leland\">[[John Leland (journalist)|Leland, John]]. ''[https://www.nytimes.com/2002/03/07/garden/going-home-with-cassandra-wilson-jazz-diva-follows-sound-of-her-roots.html?ref=cassandra_wilson&pagewanted=2 GOING HOME WITH: Cassandra Wilson; Jazz Diva Follows Sound of Her Roots],'' ''[[The New York Times]]'', March 7, 2002</ref>\n\nWilson\u2019s earliest formal musical education consisted of classical lessons; she studied piano from the age of six to thirteen and played clarinet in the middle school concert and [[marching band]]s.<ref name=\"Leland\" /> When she was tired of this training, she asked her father to teach her the guitar. Instead, he gave her a lesson in self-reliance, suggesting she study [[Mel Bay]] method books. Wilson explored guitar on her own, developing what she has described as an \"intuitive\" approach. During this time she began writing her own songs, adopting a [[folk music|folk style]]. She also appeared in the musical theater productions, including ''[[The Wizard of Oz (adaptations)|The Wizard of Oz]]'' as Dorothy, crossing racial lines in a recently desegregated school system.\n\nWilson attended [[Millsaps College]] and [[Jackson State University]]. She graduated with a degree in [[mass communications]]. Outside of the classroom, she spent her nights working with R&B, funk, and pop [[cover band]]s, also singing in local coffeehouses. The Black Arts Music Society, founded by John Reese and [[Alvin Fielder]], provided her with her first opportunities to perform [[bebop]]. In 2007, Wilson received her Ph.D in Arts from [[Millsaps College]].\n\nIn 1981, she moved to New Orleans for a position as assistant public affairs director for the local television station, WDSU. She did not stay long. Working with mentors who included elder statesmen Earl Turbinton, [[Alvin Batiste]], and [[Ellis Marsalis, Jr.|Ellis Marsalis]], Wilson found encouragement to seriously pursue jazz performance and moved to New York City the following year.\n\n==Musical association with M-Base==\nIn New York, Wilson's focus turned towards improvisation. Heavily influenced by singers [[Abbey Lincoln]] and [[Betty Carter]], she fine-tuned her vocal phrasing and [[scat singing|scat]] while studying [[ear training]] with trombonist [[Grachan Moncur, III]]. Frequenting jam sessions under the tutelage of pianist [[Sadik Hakim]], a [[Charlie Parker]] alumnus, she met alto saxophonist [[Steve Coleman]], who encouraged her to look beyond the standard jazz repertoire in favor of developing original material. She would become the vocalist and one of the founding members of the [[M-Base]] collective in which Coleman was the leading figure, a stylistic outgrowth of the [[Association for the Advancement of Creative Musicians]] (AACM) and [[Black Artists Group]] (BAG) that re-imagined the grooves of funk and soul within the context of traditional and [[avant-garde jazz]]. Peter Watrous in an article for ''[[The New York Times]]'' states:\n\n<blockquote>The M-Base group in Brooklyn, working with both jazz and pop forms, makes music that at first sounds like funk from the 1970s. Like the music played by Mr. Marsalis (and his brother [[Wynton Marsalis|Wynton]]) the music made by M-Base - Steve Coleman, with [[Greg Osby]], Cassandra Wilson and [[Geri Allen]] \u2013 is, at its best, filled with subtle ideas working behind the mask of popular music. In Mr. Coleman's group a singer is supported by an electric bass, guitar, drums and electric keyboards, a shiny musical mix that has familiar rock and funk references; yet, because of all its rhythmic and metric manipulations, sounds new.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1989/12/31/arts/pop-view-private-codes-enliven-jazz.html |title=POP VIEW: Private Codes Enliven Jazz |first=Peter |last=Watrous |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=December 31, 1989}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nAlthough the voice \u2013 typically treated as the focal point of any arrangement in which it is included \u2013 was not an obvious choice for M-Base's complex textures or harmonically elaborated melodies, Wilson wove herself into the fabric of these settings with wordless improv and lyrics. She can be heard on Coleman's debut as a leader ''Motherland Pulse'' (1985), then as member of his ''Five Elements'' on ''On the Edge of Tomorrow'' (1986), ''World Expansion'' (1986), ''Sine Die'' (1987), and on M-Base Collective's sole recording as a large ensemble ''Anatomy of a Groove'' (1992).\n\nAt the same time, Wilson toured with avant-garde trio [[Air (jazz group)|New Air]] featuring alto saxophonist [[Henry Threadgill]] and recorded ''[[Air Show No. 1]]'' (1987) in Italy. A decade her senior and an AACM member, Threadgill has been lauded as a composer for his ability to transcend stylistic boundaries, a trait he and Wilson share.\n\n==Solo career==\n<!-- Image with unknown copyright status removed: [[File:Cwilson2008.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Cassandra Wilson|{{Deletable image-caption|1=Saturday, April 25, 2009|date=May 2012}}]] -->\nLike fellow M-Base artists, Wilson signed to the Munich-based, independent label [[JMT Records|JMT]]. She released her first recording as a leader ''[[Point of View (Cassandra Wilson album)|Point of View]]'' in 1986. Like the majority of her JMT albums that followed, originals by Wilson in keeping with M-Base dominated these sessions; she would also record material by and co-written with Coleman, [[Jean-Paul Bourelly]], and James Weidman as well as a few standards. Her throaty [[contralto]] gradually emerges over the course of these recordings, making its way to the foreground. She developed a remarkable ability to stretch and bend pitches, elongate syllables, manipulate tone and timbre from dusky to hollow.<ref>[[Brian Priestley]], [[Digby Fairweather]], [[Ian Carr]]. ''Jazz, The Rough Guide'', 2nd Edition March 2000</ref>\n\nWhile these recordings established her as a serious musician, Wilson received her first broad critical acclaim for the album of standards recorded in the middle of this period, ''[[Blue Skies (Cassandra Wilson album)|Blue Skies]]'' (1988). Her signing with [[Blue Note Records]] in 1993 marked a crucial turning point in her career and major breakthrough to audiences beyond jazz with albums selling in the hundreds of thousands of copies.\n\nBeginning with ''[[Blue Light 'Til Dawn]]'' (1993) her repertoire moved towards a broad synthesis of blues, pop, jazz, world music, and country. Although she continued to perform originals and standards, she adopted songs as diverse as [[Robert Johnson (musician)|Robert Johnson]]'s \"[[Come On in My Kitchen]]\", [[Joni Mitchell]]'s \"Black Crow\", [[The Monkees]]' \"[[Last Train to Clarksville]]\", and [[Hank Williams]]' \"[[I'm So Lonesome I Could Cry]]\".\n\nWilson's 1996 album ''[[New Moon Daughter]]'' won the [[Grammy]] for [[Best Jazz Vocal Performance]]. In 1997, she recorded and toured as a featured vocalist with [[Wynton Marsalis]]' [[Pulitzer Prize]] winning composition, ''[[Blood on the Fields]]''.\n\n[[Miles Davis]] was one of Wilson's greatest influences. In 1989, Wilson performed as the opening act for Davis at the [[JVC Jazz Festival]] in Chicago. In 1999 she produced ''[[Traveling Miles]]'' as a tribute to Davis. The album developed from a series of jazz concerts that she performed at [[Lincoln Center]] in November 1997 in Davis' honor, and includes three selections based on Davis' own compositions, from which Wilson adapted the original themes.\n\n==Personal life==\nWilson was married to Anthony Wilson from 1981 to 1983.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/09/29/garden/in-the-studio-with-cassandra-wilson-singing-a-song-of-the-south.html | work=The New York Times | title=IN THE STUDIO WITH: Cassandra Wilson; Singing a Song of the South | first=Charisse | last=Jones | date=September 29, 1994}}</ref>\n\nShe has a son, Jeris, born in the late 1980s. Her song \"Out Loud (Jeris' Blues)\" on the album ''She Who Weeps'' is dedicated to him. For many years she and her son lived in New York City's [[Sugar Hill, Manhattan|Sugar Hill]], in an apartment that once belonged to [[Count Basie]], [[Lena Horne]] and the boxer [[Joe Louis]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.metro.co.uk | work=The Metro | title=The Big Interview Cassandra Wilson | first=John | last=Lewis | date=November 22, 2010}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2000 to 2003 Wilson was married to actor [[Isaach de Bankol\u00e9]], who directed her in the concert film ''Traveling Miles: Cassandra Wilson'' (2000).\n\nWilson and her mother are members of [[Alpha Kappa Alpha]] sorority.\n\n==Awards and honors==\n* 1994\u20131996: Female Jazz Vocalist of the Year, ''[[Down Beat]]'' \n* 1997: [[Grammy Award for Best Jazz Vocal Album|Grammy Award for Best Jazz Vocal Performance]], ''[[New Moon Daughter]]''\n* 1999: Miles Davis Prize, [[Montreal International Jazz Festival]]\n* 2001: \"America's Best Singer\", ''[[Time Magazine|Time]]''\n* 2003: [[Honorary doctorate]] in the Arts, [[Millsaps College]]\n* 2009: [[Grammy Award for Best Jazz Vocal Album]], ''[[Loverly]]''\n* 2010: Added to [[Mississippi Blues Trail]]<ref name=\"Trail\">{{cite web|title=Cassandra Wilson|url=http://www.msbluestrail.org/blues-trail-markers/cassandra-wilson|website=Mississippi Blues Trail|accessdate=15 September 2016}}</ref>\n* 2010: Best Vocal Album, [[NPR Music]] Jazz Critics Poll 2010, ''[[Silver Pony]]''\n* 2011: Best Traditional Jazz Album, [[BET]] Soul Train Award, ''Silver Pony''\n* 2015: Honorary doctorate in Fine Arts, [[The New School]]\n* 2015: Spirit of Ireland Award, Irish Arts Centre\n\n==Discography==\n===As leader===\n* ''[[Point of View (Cassandra Wilson album)|Point of View]]'' (JMT, 1986)\n* ''[[Days Aweigh]]'' (JMT, 1987)\n* ''[[Blue Skies (Cassandra Wilson album)|Blue Skies]]'' (JMT, 1988)\n* ''[[Jumpworld]]'' (JMT, 1990)\n* ''[[Live (Cassandra Wilson album)|Live]]'' (JMT, 1991)\n* ''[[She Who Weeps]]'' (JMT, 1991)\n* ''[[Dance to the Drums Again]]'' (DIW, 1992)\n* ''[[After the Beginning Again]]'' (JMT, 1992)\n* ''[[Blue Light 'til Dawn]]'' (Blue Note, 1993)\n* ''[[New Moon Daughter]]'' (Blue Note, 1995)\n* ''[[Rendezvous (Jacky Terrasson and Cassandra Wilson album)|Rendezvous]]'' with Jacky Terrasson (Blue Note, 1997)\n* ''[[Traveling Miles]]'' (Blue Note, 1999)\n* ''[[Belly of the Sun]]'' (Blue Note, 2002)\n* ''[[Glamoured]]'' (Blue Note, 2003)\n* ''[[Thunderbird (Cassandra Wilson album)|Thunderbird]]'' (Blue Note, 2006)\n* ''[[Loverly]]'' (Blue Note, 2008)\n* ''[[Silver Pony]]'' (Blue Note, 2010)\n* ''[[Another Country (Cassandra Wilson album)|Another Country]]'' (eOne, 2012)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jazztimes.com/articles/29789-cassandra-wilson-signs-to-eone-music |title=Cassandra Wilson Signs to eOne Music|website=JazzTimes|date=March 26, 2012|accessdate=May 23, 2012}}</ref>)\n* ''[[Coming Forth by Day (Cassandra Wilson album)|Coming Forth by Day]]'' ([[Legacy Recordings|Legacy]], 2015)<ref>{{cite web|last1=Tamarkin|first1=Jeff|title=Legacy Recordings Signs Cassandra Wilson|url=http://jazztimes.com/articles/147549-legacy-recordings-signs-cassandra-wilson|website=jazztimes.com|accessdate=2014-12-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222165447/http://jazztimes.com/articles/147549-legacy-recordings-signs-cassandra-wilson|archive-date=December 22, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n'''Compilations'''\n* ''Songbook'' (JMT, 1995)\n* ''[[Sings Standards]]'' (Verve, 2002)\n* ''Love Phases Dimensions: From the JMT Years'' ([[Edel AG|Edel]], 2004)\n* ''[[Closer to You: The Pop Side]]'' (Blue Note, 2009)\n\n===As guest===\n'''With [[Steve Coleman]]'''\n* ''[[Motherland Pulse]]'' (JMT, 1985)\n* ''[[On the Edge of Tomorrow]]'' (JMT, 1986)\n* ''[[World Expansion]]'' (JMT, 1987)\n* ''Sine Die'' ([[Pangea Recordings|Pangaea]], 1988)\n* ''Rhythm People'' (RCA, 1990)\n* ''[[Black Science (Steve Coleman album)|Black Science]]'' (Novus, 1991)\n* ''[[Drop Kick (album)|Drop Kick]]'' (Novus, 1992)\n* ''The Ascension to Light'' (BMG France, 1999)\n\n'''With [[Wynton Marsalis]]'''\n* ''[[Blood on the Fields]]'' (Columbia, 1997)\n* ''[[Reeltime (album)|Reeltime]]'' ([[Sony Music|Sony]], 1999)\n\n'''With [[The Roots]]'''\n* ''[[Do You Want More?!!!??!]]'' ([[DGC Records|DGC]], 1994)\n* ''[[Illadelph Halflife]]'' (DGC, 1996)\n\n'''With others'''\n* [[Air (jazz group)|New Air]], ''[[Air Show No. 1]]'' (Black Saint, 1986)\n* [[Don Byron]], ''A Fine Line: Arias & Lieder'' (Blue Note, 2000)\n* [[Terence Blanchard]], ''[[Let's Get Lost (album)|Let's Get Lost]]'' (Sony, 2001)\n* [[Terri Lyne Carrington]], ''[[The Mosaic Project (album)|The Mosaic Project]]'' ([[Concord Jazz]], 2011)\n* [[Regina Carter]], ''Rhythms of the Heart'' (Verve, 1999)\n* [[Olu Dara]], ''[[Neighborhoods (Olu Dara album)|Neighborhoods]]'' (Atlantic, 2001)\n* [[Kurt Elling]], ''[[The Messenger (Kurt Elling album)|The Messenger]]'' (Blue Note, 1997)\n* [[Robin Eubanks]], ''[[Karma (Robin Eubanks album)|Karma]]'' (JMT, 1991)\n* [[Bill Frisell]] & [[Elvis Costello]], ''[[The Sweetest Punch]]'' ([[Decca Records|Decca]], 1999)\n* [[Charlie Haden]] Quartet West, ''[[Sophisticated Ladies (album)|Sophisticated Ladies]]'' ([[EmArcy Records|EmArcy]], 2010)\n* [[Dave Holland]], ''[[Dream of the Elders]]'' ([[ECM Records|ECM]], 1995)\n* [[Javon Jackson]], ''A Look Within'' (Blue Note, 1996)\n* [[Angelique Kidjo]], ''Oremi'' ([[Island Records|Island]], 1998)\n* [[M-Base]] Collective, ''Anatomy of a Groove'' (Columbia, 1992)\n* [[David Murray (saxophonist)|David Murray]] Black Saint Quartet, ''Sacred Ground'' ([[Justin Time Records|Justin Time]], 2007)\n* [[Meshell Ndegeocello]], ''[[The Spirit Music Jamia: Dance of the Infidel]]'' ([[Shanachie Records|Shanachie]], 2005)\n* [[Greg Osby]], ''[[Season of Renewal]]'' (JMT, 1990)\n* [[Courtney Pine]], ''Modern Day Jazz Stories'' ([[Antilles Records|Antilles]], 1995)\n* [[David Sanchez (musician)|David Sanchez]], ''Street Scenes'' (Columbia, 1996)\n* [[Steve Turre]], ''Steve Turre'' (Verve, 1997)\n* [[Luther Vandross]], ''I Know'' ([[EMI Records|EMI]], 1998)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://www.cassandrawilson.com}}\n* {{discogs artist}}\n* {{IMDb name|id=0933147|name=Cassandra Wilson}}\n* [http://www.bluenote.com/artists/cassandra-wilson Cassandra Wilson] at [[Blue Note Records]]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110525034940/http://www.montrealjazzfest.com/artists/artist.aspx?id=510 Cassandra Wilson] at [[Montreal International Jazz Festival]]\n{{Commons category|position=left}}\n\n{{Cassandra Wilson}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wilson, Cassandra}}\n[[Category:American blues singers]]\n[[Category:American jazz singers]]\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American contraltos]]\n[[Category:American female jazz singers]]\n[[Category:American jazz songwriters]]\n[[Category:African-American female singers]]\n[[Category:African-American female singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:African-American jazz musicians]]\n[[Category:American female singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:Vocal jazz musicians]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Mississippi Blues Trail]]\n[[Category:Yoruba musicians]]\n[[Category:Jackson State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Millsaps College alumni]]\n[[Category:American people of Beninese descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Nigerian descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Welsh descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Yoruba descent]]\n[[Category:Fon people]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Jackson, Mississippi]]\n[[Category:Singers from Mississippi]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from Mississippi]]\n[[Category:20th-century American singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American musicians]]<!--as songwriter-?-->\n[[Category:21st-century American composers]]<!--as songwriter-?-->\n[[Category:20th-century American women singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women singers]]\n[[Category:Jazz musicians from Mississippi]]\n[[Category:JMT Records artists]]\n[[Category:Blue Note Records artists]]\n", "text_old": "{{BLP refimprove|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2011}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name               = Cassandra Wilson\n| image              = Cassandra Wilson.jpg\n| caption             =Cassandra Wilson in 2007\n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_name       =\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1955|12|4}}\n| birth_place        =[[Jackson, Mississippi]], U.S.\n| genre               = Jazz\n| occupation        = Singer\n| years_active     =1985\u2013present\n| label                =[[JMT Records|JMT]], [[Blue Note Records|Blue Note]]\n| associated_acts =[[M-Base|M-Base Collective]]\n| website            = {{URL|cassandrawilson.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Cassandra Wilson''' (born December 4, 1955) is an American [[jazz]] singer, songwriter, and producer from [[Jackson, Mississippi]].<ref>{{cite web  | title = Cassandra Wilson on Allmusic.com | url={{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p7837|pure_url=yes}} | accessdate =November 23, 2009 }}</ref> Described by critic [[Gary Giddins]]<ref>[[Gary Giddins|Giddins, Gary]]. (2000). ''Visions of Jazz: The First Century''. Oxford University Press, {{ISBN|978-0-19-513241-0}}, p. 643.</ref> as \"a singer blessed with an unmistakable [[timbre]] and [[Attack (music)|attack]] [who has] expanded the playing field\" by incorporating [[blues]], [[country music|country]], and [[folk music]] into her work.\n\n==Early life and career==\nCassandra Wilson is the third and youngest child of [[Herman Fowlkes, Jr.]], a guitarist, bassist, and music teacher;<ref>Litweiler, John. ''[http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/644655/Cassandra-Wilson Cassandra Wilson],'' [[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica Online]]</ref> and Mary McDaniel, an elementary school teacher who earned her PhD in education. Her ancestry includes [[Fon people|Fon]], [[Yoruba people|Yoruba]], [[Irish people|Irish]] and [[Welsh people|Welsh]]. Between her mother\u2019s love for [[Motown]] and her father\u2019s dedication to jazz, Wilson\u2019s parents sparked her early interest in music.<ref name=\"Leland\">[[John Leland (journalist)|Leland, John]]. ''[https://www.nytimes.com/2002/03/07/garden/going-home-with-cassandra-wilson-jazz-diva-follows-sound-of-her-roots.html?ref=cassandra_wilson&pagewanted=2 GOING HOME WITH: Cassandra Wilson; Jazz Diva Follows Sound of Her Roots],'' ''[[The New York Times]]'', March 7, 2002</ref>\n\nWilson\u2019s earliest formal musical education consisted of classical lessons; she studied piano from the age of six to thirteen and played clarinet in the middle school concert and [[marching band]]s.<ref name=\"Leland\" /> When she was tired of this training, she asked her father to teach her the guitar. Instead, he gave her a lesson in self-reliance, suggesting she study [[Mel Bay]] method books. Wilson explored guitar on her own, developing what she has described as an \"intuitive\" approach. During this time she began writing her own songs, adopting a [[folk music|folk style]]. She also appeared in the musical theater productions, including ''[[The Wizard of Oz (adaptations)|The Wizard of Oz]]'' as Dorothy, crossing racial lines in a recently desegregated school system.\n\nWilson attended [[Millsaps College]] and [[Jackson State University]]. She graduated with a degree in [[mass communications]]. Outside of the classroom, she spent her nights working with R&B, funk, and pop [[cover band]]s, also singing in local coffeehouses. The Black Arts Music Society, founded by John Reese and [[Alvin Fielder]], provided her with her first opportunities to perform [[bebop]]. In 2007, Wilson received her Ph.D in Arts from [[Millsaps College]].\n\nIn 1981, she moved to New Orleans for a position as assistant public affairs director for the local television station, WDSU. She did not stay long. Working with mentors who included elder statesmen Earl Turbinton, [[Alvin Batiste]], and [[Ellis Marsalis, Jr.|Ellis Marsalis]], Wilson found encouragement to seriously pursue jazz performance and moved to New York City the following year.\n\n==Musical association with M-Base==\nIn New York, Wilson's focus turned towards improvisation. Heavily influenced by singers [[Abbey Lincoln]] and [[Betty Carter]], she fine-tuned her vocal phrasing and [[scat singing|scat]] while studying [[ear training]] with trombonist [[Grachan Moncur, III]]. Frequenting jam sessions under the tutelage of pianist [[Sadik Hakim]], a [[Charlie Parker]] alumnus, she met alto saxophonist [[Steve Coleman]], who encouraged her to look beyond the standard jazz repertoire in favor of developing original material. She would become the vocalist and one of the founding members of the [[M-Base]] collective in which Coleman was the leading figure, a stylistic outgrowth of the [[Association for the Advancement of Creative Musicians]] (AACM) and [[Black Artists Group]] (BAG) that re-imagined the grooves of funk and soul within the context of traditional and [[avant-garde jazz]]. Peter Watrous in an article for ''[[The New York Times]]'' states:\n\n<blockquote>The M-Base group in Brooklyn, working with both jazz and pop forms, makes music that at first sounds like funk from the 1970s. Like the music played by Mr. Marsalis (and his brother [[Wynton Marsalis|Wynton]]) the music made by M-Base - Steve Coleman, with [[Greg Osby]], Cassandra Wilson and [[Geri Allen]] \u2013 is, at its best, filled with subtle ideas working behind the mask of popular music. In Mr. Coleman's group a singer is supported by an electric bass, guitar, drums and electric keyboards, a shiny musical mix that has familiar rock and funk references; yet, because of all its rhythmic and metric manipulations, sounds new.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1989/12/31/arts/pop-view-private-codes-enliven-jazz.html |title=POP VIEW: Private Codes Enliven Jazz |first=Peter |last=Watrous |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=December 31, 1989}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nAlthough the voice \u2013 typically treated as the focal point of any arrangement in which it is included \u2013 was not an obvious choice for M-Base's complex textures or harmonically elaborated melodies, Wilson wove herself into the fabric of these settings with wordless improv and lyrics. She can be heard on Coleman's debut as a leader ''Motherland Pulse'' (1985), then as member of his ''Five Elements'' on ''On the Edge of Tomorrow'' (1986), ''World Expansion'' (1986), ''Sine Die'' (1987), and on M-Base Collective's sole recording as a large ensemble ''Anatomy of a Groove'' (1992).\n\nAt the same time, Wilson toured with avant-garde trio [[Air (jazz group)|New Air]] featuring alto saxophonist [[Henry Threadgill]] and recorded ''[[Air Show No. 1]]'' (1987) in Italy. A decade her senior and an AACM member, Threadgill has been lauded as a composer for his ability to transcend stylistic boundaries, a trait he and Wilson share.\n\n==Solo career==\n<!-- Image with unknown copyright status removed: [[File:Cwilson2008.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Cassandra Wilson|{{Deletable image-caption|1=Saturday, April 25, 2009|date=May 2012}}]] -->\nLike fellow M-Base artists, Wilson signed to the Munich-based, independent label [[JMT Records|JMT]]. She released her first recording as a leader ''[[Point of View (Cassandra Wilson album)|Point of View]]'' in 1986. Like the majority of her JMT albums that followed, originals by Wilson in keeping with M-Base dominated these sessions; she would also record material by and co-written with Coleman, [[Jean-Paul Bourelly]], and James Weidman as well as a few standards. Her throaty [[contralto]] gradually emerges over the course of these recordings, making its way to the foreground. She developed a remarkable ability to stretch and bend pitches, elongate syllables, manipulate tone and timbre from dusky to hollow.<ref>[[Brian Priestley]], [[Digby Fairweather]], [[Ian Carr]]. ''Jazz, The Rough Guide'', 2nd Edition March 2000</ref>\n\nWhile these recordings established her as a serious musician, Wilson received her first broad critical acclaim for the album of standards recorded in the middle of this period, ''[[Blue Skies (Cassandra Wilson album)|Blue Skies]]'' (1988). Her signing with [[Blue Note Records]] in 1993 marked a crucial turning point in her career and major breakthrough to audiences beyond jazz with albums selling in the hundreds of thousands of copies.\n\nBeginning with ''[[Blue Light 'Til Dawn]]'' (1993) her repertoire moved towards a broad synthesis of blues, pop, jazz, world music, and country. Although she continued to perform originals and standards, she adopted songs as diverse as [[Robert Johnson (musician)|Robert Johnson]]'s \"[[Come On in My Kitchen]]\", [[Joni Mitchell]]'s \"Black Crow\", [[The Monkees]]' \"[[Last Train to Clarksville]]\", and [[Hank Williams]]' \"[[I'm So Lonesome I Could Cry]]\".\n\nWilson's 1996 album ''[[New Moon Daughter]]'' won the [[Grammy]] for [[Best Jazz Vocal Performance]]. In 1997, she recorded and toured as a featured vocalist with [[Wynton Marsalis]]' [[Pulitzer Prize]] winning composition, ''[[Blood on the Fields]]''.\n\n[[Miles Davis]] was one of Wilson's greatest influences. In 1989, Wilson performed as the opening act for Davis at the [[JVC Jazz Festival]] in Chicago. In 1999 she produced ''[[Traveling Miles]]'' as a tribute to Davis. The album developed from a series of jazz concerts that she performed at [[Lincoln Center]] in November 1997 in Davis' honor, and includes three selections based on Davis' own compositions, from which Wilson adapted the original themes.\n\n==Personal life==\nWilson was married to Anthony Wilson from 1981 to 1983.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/09/29/garden/in-the-studio-with-cassandra-wilson-singing-a-song-of-the-south.html | work=The New York Times | title=IN THE STUDIO WITH: Cassandra Wilson; Singing a Song of the South | first=Charisse | last=Jones | date=September 29, 1994}}</ref>\n\nShe has a son, Jeris, born in the late 1980s. Her song \"Out Loud (Jeris' Blues)\" on the album ''She Who Weeps'' is dedicated to him. For many years she and her son lived in New York City's [[Sugar Hill, Manhattan|Sugar Hill]], in an apartment that once belonged to [[Count Basie]], [[Lena Horne]] and the boxer [[Joe Louis]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.metro.co.uk | work=The Metro | title=The Big Interview Cassandra Wilson | first=John | last=Lewis | date=November 22, 2010}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2000 to 2003 Wilson was married to actor [[Isaach de Bankol\u00e9]], who directed her in the concert film ''Traveling Miles: Cassandra Wilson'' (2000).\n\nWilson and her mother are members of [[Alpha Kappa Alpha]] sorority.\n\n==Awards and honors==\n* 1994\u20131996: Female Jazz Vocalist of the Year, ''[[Down Beat]]'' \n* 1997: [[Grammy Award for Best Jazz Vocal Album|Grammy Award for Best Jazz Vocal Performance]], ''[[New Moon Daughter]]''\n* 1999: Miles Davis Prize, [[Montreal International Jazz Festival]]\n* 2001: \"America's Best Singer\", ''[[Time Magazine|Time]]''\n* 2003: [[Honorary doctorate]] in the Arts, [[Millsaps College]]\n* 2009: [[Grammy Award for Best Jazz Vocal Album]], ''[[Loverly]]''\n* 2010: Added to [[Mississippi Blues Trail]]<ref name=\"Trail\">{{cite web|title=Cassandra Wilson|url=http://www.msbluestrail.org/blues-trail-markers/cassandra-wilson|website=Mississippi Blues Trail|accessdate=15 September 2016}}</ref>\n* 2010: Best Vocal Album, [[NPR Music]] Jazz Critics Poll 2010, ''[[Silver Pony]]''\n* 2011: Best Traditional Jazz Album, [[BET]] Soul Train Award, ''Silver Pony''\n* 2015: Honorary doctorate in Fine Arts, [[The New School]]\n* 2015: Spirit of Ireland Award, Irish Arts Centre\n\n==Discography==\n===As leader===\n* ''[[Point of View (Cassandra Wilson album)|Point of View]]'' (JMT, 1986)\n* ''[[Days Aweigh]]'' (JMT, 1987)\n* ''[[Blue Skies (Cassandra Wilson album)|Blue Skies]]'' (JMT, 1988)\n* ''[[Jumpworld]]'' (JMT, 1990)\n* ''[[Live (Cassandra Wilson album)|Live]]'' (JMT, 1991)\n* ''[[She Who Weeps]]'' (JMT, 1991)\n* ''[[Dance to the Drums Again]]'' (DIW, 1992)\n* ''[[After the Beginning Again]]'' (JMT, 1992)\n* ''[[Blue Light 'til Dawn]]'' (Blue Note, 1993)\n* ''[[New Moon Daughter]]'' (Blue Note, 1995)\n* ''[[Rendezvous (Jacky Terrasson and Cassandra Wilson album)|Rendezvous]]'' with Jacky Terrasson (Blue Note, 1997)\n* ''[[Traveling Miles]]'' (Blue Note, 1999)\n* ''[[Belly of the Sun]]'' (Blue Note, 2002)\n* ''[[Glamoured]]'' (Blue Note, 2003)\n* ''[[Thunderbird (Cassandra Wilson album)|Thunderbird]]'' (Blue Note, 2006)\n* ''[[Loverly]]'' (Blue Note, 2008)\n* ''[[Silver Pony]]'' (Blue Note, 2010)\n* ''[[Another Country (Cassandra Wilson album)|Another Country]]'' (eOne, 2012)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jazztimes.com/articles/29789-cassandra-wilson-signs-to-eone-music |title=Cassandra Wilson Signs to eOne Music|website=JazzTimes|date=March 26, 2012|accessdate=May 23, 2012}}</ref>)\n* ''[[Coming Forth by Day (Cassandra Wilson album)|Coming Forth by Day]]'' ([[Legacy Recordings|Legacy]], 2015)<ref>{{cite web|last1=Tamarkin|first1=Jeff|title=Legacy Recordings Signs Cassandra Wilson|url=http://jazztimes.com/articles/147549-legacy-recordings-signs-cassandra-wilson|website=jazztimes.com|accessdate=2014-12-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222165447/http://jazztimes.com/articles/147549-legacy-recordings-signs-cassandra-wilson|archive-date=December 22, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n'''Compilations'''\n* ''Songbook'' (JMT, 1995)\n* ''[[Sings Standards]]'' (Verve, 2002)\n* ''Love Phases Dimensions: From the JMT Years'' ([[Edel AG|Edel]], 2004)\n* ''[[Closer to You: The Pop Side]]'' (Blue Note, 2009)\n\n===As guest===\n'''With [[Steve Coleman]]'''\n* ''[[Motherland Pulse]]'' (JMT, 1985)\n* ''[[On the Edge of Tomorrow]]'' (JMT, 1986)\n* ''[[World Expansion]]'' (JMT, 1987)\n* ''Sine Die'' ([[Pangea Recordings|Pangaea]], 1988)\n* ''Rhythm People'' (RCA, 1990)\n* ''[[Black Science (Steve Coleman album)|Black Science]]'' (Novus, 1991)\n* ''[[Drop Kick (album)|Drop Kick]]'' (Novus, 1992)\n* ''The Ascension to Light'' (BMG France, 1999)\n\n'''With [[Wynton Marsalis]]'''\n* ''[[Blood on the Fields]]'' (Columbia, 1997)\n* ''[[Reeltime (album)|Reeltime]]'' ([[Sony Music|Sony]], 1999)\n\n'''With [[The Roots]]'''\n* ''[[Do You Want More?!!!??!]]'' ([[DGC Records|DGC]], 1994)\n* ''[[Illadelph Halflife]]'' (DGC, 1996)\n\n'''With others'''\n* [[Air (jazz group)|New Air]], ''[[Air Show No. 1]]'' (Black Saint, 1986)\n* [[Don Byron]], ''A Fine Line: Arias & Lieder'' (Blue Note, 2000)\n* [[Terence Blanchard]], ''[[Let's Get Lost (album)|Let's Get Lost]]'' (Sony, 2001)\n* [[Terri Lyne Carrington]], ''[[The Mosaic Project (album)|The Mosaic Project]]'' ([[Concord Jazz]], 2011)\n* [[Regina Carter]], ''Rhythms of the Heart'' (Verve, 1999)\n* [[Olu Dara]], ''[[Neighborhoods (Olu Dara album)|Neighborhoods]]'' (Atlantic, 2001)\n* [[Kurt Elling]], ''[[The Messenger (Kurt Elling album)|The Messenger]]'' (Blue Note, 1997)\n* [[Robin Eubanks]], ''[[Karma (Robin Eubanks album)|Karma]]'' (JMT, 1991)\n* [[Bill Frisell]] & [[Elvis Costello]], ''[[The Sweetest Punch]]'' ([[Decca Records|Decca]], 1999)\n* [[Charlie Haden]] Quartet West, ''[[Sophisticated Ladies (album)|Sophisticated Ladies]]'' ([[EmArcy Records|EmArcy]], 2010)\n* [[Dave Holland]], ''[[Dream of the Elders]]'' ([[ECM Records|ECM]], 1995)\n* [[Javon Jackson]], ''A Look Within'' (Blue Note, 1996)\n* [[Angelique Kidjo]], ''Oremi'' ([[Island Records|Island]], 1998)\n* [[M-Base]] Collective, ''Anatomy of a Groove'' (Columbia, 1992)\n* [[David Murray (saxophonist)|David Murray]] Black Saint Quartet, ''Sacred Ground'' ([[Justin Time Records|Justin Time]], 2007)\n* [[Meshell Ndegeocello]], ''[[The Spirit Music Jamia: Dance of the Infidel]]'' ([[Shanachie Records|Shanachie]], 2005)\n* [[Greg Osby]], ''[[Season of Renewal]]'' (JMT, 1990)\n* [[Courtney Pine]], ''Modern Day Jazz Stories'' ([[Antilles Records|Antilles]], 1995)\n* [[David Sanchez (musician)|David Sanchez]], ''Street Scenes'' (Columbia, 1996)\n* [[Steve Turre]], ''Steve Turre'' (Verve, 1997)\n* [[Luther Vandross]], ''I Know'' ([[EMI Records|EMI]], 1998)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://www.cassandrawilson.com}}\n* {{discogs artist}}\n* {{IMDb name|id=0933147|name=Cassandra Wilson}}\n* [http://www.bluenote.com/artists/cassandra-wilson Cassandra Wilson] at [[Blue Note Records]]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110525034940/http://www.montrealjazzfest.com/artists/artist.aspx?id=510 Cassandra Wilson] at [[Montreal International Jazz Festival]]\n{{Commons category|position=left}}\n\n{{Cassandra Wilson}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wilson, Cassandra}}\n[[Category:American blues singers]]\n[[Category:American jazz singers]]\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American contraltos]]\n[[Category:American female jazz singers]]\n[[Category:American jazz songwriters]]\n[[Category:African-American female singers]]\n[[Category:African-American female singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:African-American jazz musicians]]\n[[Category:American female singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:Vocal jazz musicians]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Mississippi Blues Trail]]\n[[Category:Yoruba musicians]]\n[[Category:Jackson State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Millsaps College alumni]]\n[[Category:American people of Beninese descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Nigerian descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Welsh descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Yoruba descent]]\n[[Category:Fon people]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Jackson, Mississippi]]\n[[Category:Singers from Mississippi]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from Mississippi]