w.internews.org/prs/2009/20090513_afghan.shtm\n |archivedate = 2009-05-19\n |url-status     = dead\n}}</ref><ref name=TorontoStar2009-08-15>\n{{cite news\n |url         = https://www.thestar.com/news/world/article/681650\n |title       = Taking on Afghanistan's patriarchy: Two women seeking presidency subjected to smears and hostility in fight for reform\n |date        = 2009-08-15\n |author      = Rosie Dimanno\n |publisher   = [[Toronto Star]]\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20090816173547/http://www.thestar.com/news/world/article/681650\n |archivedate = 2009-08-16\n |url-status     = dead\n}}</ref><ref name=Npr>\n{{cite news\n |url         = https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=111349105\n |title       = Candidates' Stories Reflect Afghanistan's Struggle\n |date        = 2009-07-30\n |publisher   = [[National Public Radio]]\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20091009121428/http://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=111349105\n |archivedate = 2009-10-09\n |accessdate  = 2009-08-02\n |url-status     = dead\n}}</ref><ref name=Ap2009-08-05>\n{{cite news\n |url         = https://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5i-UmwryIsQh6f1HpnLsKuCBbG7xgD99SS3U80\n |title       = 2 women vie for Afghan presidency\n |date        = 2009-08-05\n |agency      = Associated Press\n |df          = \n}}{{dead link|date=December 2017|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\nHer running mate was Mohammad Nasim Darmand.<ref name=HuffingtonPost2Women>\n {{cite news\n| url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2009/08/05/shahla-atta-frozan-fana-2_n_252001.html\n| title=Shahla Atta, Frozan Fana: 2 Women Among Those Vying For Afghan Presidency\n| date=2009-05-08\n| author=Heidi Vogt\n| publisher=Huffington Post\n| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090909135229/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2009/08/05/shahla-atta-frozan-fana-2_n_252001.html\n| archivedate=2009-09-09\n}}</ref><ref name=Afp2009-05-15>\n{{cite news\n |url         = https://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5gJqqwsD5Y0A7kZPyMt0eXKx3RpVw\n |title       = Madam President in Afghanistan?\n |date        = 2009-05-15\n |publisher   = [[Agence France Presse]]\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20100417124620/http://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5gJqqwsD5Y0A7kZPyMt0eXKx3RpVw\n |archivedate = 2010-04-17\n |url-status     = dead\n}}</ref>\nShe had never held political office before. However, she is the widow of [[Abdul Rahman (Afghan minister)|Abdul Rahman]], the assassinated Afghan Aviation Minister.\n\nFana is an [[Orthopaedic surgeon]].<ref name=HuffingtonPost2Women/>\n\nFana was criticized for using campaign posters that had her picture on it.<ref name=Bbc2009-08-13/>\n\nOne other woman was a candidate for President in 2009, [[Shahla Atta]].<ref name=HuffingtonPost2Women/>  \nShe was already a member of the [[Wolesi Jirga]], Afghanistan's National Legislature.\nAfter [[Massouda Jalal]] came sixth out of eighteen presidential candidates in 2004 then President [[Hamid Karzai]] appointed her [[Afghan Women's Affairs Minister]].\n\nAccording to Rosie DiManno, writing in the ''[[Toronto Star]]'', Fana had difficulty campaigning due to her gender.<ref name=TorontoStar2009-08-15/>\nFana described being ignored by security officials, when asked for security details when she scheduled public meetings, so much of her campaign revolved around inviting guests to her home.\n\nDiManno described Fana's concerns that her husband had been murdered by elements within Karzai's administration, who saw him as a potential candidate for president.<ref name=TorontoStar2009-08-15/>\n\nDiManno quoted Fana on the difficulties Fana enoountered acting as high-profile woman who could serve as a role-model to other women:<ref name=TorontoStar2009-08-15/> ''\"These men don't even want me to practise as a doctor. There is so much risk for women, so much violence against them in their own homes. Who cares? Not the men in power. They do nothing.''\n\nPreliminary voting results placed Fana eighth in a [[List of candidates in the Afghan presidential election, 2009|field of thirty-two]].<ref name=Sabawoon>\n{{cite news\n |url         = http://www.sabawoon.com/index.php?page=afghanelection\n |title       = Preliminary Result of Afghanistan Presidential Contest\n |date        = 2009-08-20\n |publisher   = [[Sabawoon online]]\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20090803012110/http://www.sabawoon.com/index.php?page=afghanelection\n |archivedate = 2009-08-03\n |url-status     = dead\n}}</ref> The 8,159 votes for Fana represented less than 0.5% of the total votes cast.<ref name=Sabawoon/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20011129022125/http://www.frozan.org/ www.frozan.org/]\n\n<!--\n    The following categories contain articles about individuals who almost \n    all have names that follow the style for Arabic names.\n    Arabic names don't have European style surnames that are inherited, father to son.\n    So, there is no point changing the order in which they are sorted in the categories.\n\n    Thanks!\n-->\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fana, Frozan}}\n[[Category:Members of the House of the People (Afghanistan)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth uncertain]]\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:Afghan women in politics]]\n", "name_user": "Chris the speller", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:replaced: President \u2192 president", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frozan_Fana"}
{"title_page": "Wegmans", "text_new": "{{short description|Supermarket chain in the northeastern United States}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2017}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Wegmans Food Markets, Inc.\n| logo = File:WegmansLogo.svg\n| logo_size = 250px\n| image = Wegmans in Lancaster PA.jpg\n| image_size = 250px\n| image_caption = The exterior of a typical Wegmans, pictured in 2018 in Lancaster, Pennsylvania.\n| former_name = Rochester Fruit and Vegetable Company (1916-1930)\n| type = {{flat list|\n* Private\n* [[family business]]\n}}\n| industry = [[Grocery|Retail (Grocery)]]\n| founder = {{plain list|\n* John Wegman\n* Walter Wegman\n}}\n| founded = {{start date and age|1916}} in [[Rochester, New York]], U.S.\n| location_city = [[Rochester, New York]]\n| location_country = U.S.\n| num_locations = 101<ref name=\"StoreLocator\"/>\n| num_locations_year = \n| area_served = {{flat list|\n* [[Maryland]]\n* [[Massachusetts]]\n* [[New Jersey]]\n* [[New York (state)|New York]]\n* [[Pennsylvania]]\n* [[Virginia]]\n* [[North Carolina]]\n}}\n| key_people = {{plain list|\n* Colleen J. Wegman (president and CEO)\n* Nicole Wegman (Sr. Vice President)\n* Danny Wegman (chairman)\n}}\n| revenue = {{profit}} $9.2&nbsp;billion (2018)<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/companies/wegmans-food-markets/|title=Wegmans Food Markets on the Forbes Best Employers for Diversity List|work=Forbes|access-date=2018-04-28|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"hoovers\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hoovers.com/company/Wegmans_Food_Markets_Inc/cfhtji-1.html|title=!company_name! \u2013 Company Profile from Hoover's|author=|date=|publisher=|accessdate=November 29, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"2007 SN\">{{cite web|url=http://www.supermarketnews.com/sns-top-75/|title=SN's Top 75|author=|date=|publisher=|accessdate=November 29, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"wegmans\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wegmans.com/webapp/wcs/stores/servlet/CategoryDisplay?categoryId=281152&storeId=10052&catalogId=10002&langId=-1|title=Home \u2013 Wegmans|accessdate=November 29, 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151019022117/http://www.wegmans.com/webapp/wcs/stores/servlet/CategoryDisplay?categoryId=281152&storeId=10052&catalogId=10002&langId=-1|archivedate=October 19, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n| owner         = Wegman Enterprises, Inc (Wegman family (100%))\n| num_employees = 49,000\n| num_employees_year = \n| homepage = {{URL|wegmans.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Wegmans Food Markets, Inc.''' is a [[privately held company|privately held]] American [[supermarket]] chain; it is headquartered in [[Rochester, New York|Rochester]], [[New York (state)|New York]]. As of October 2019, Wegmans has 101 stores<ref name=\"StoreLocator\">{{cite web| url = https://www.wegmans.com/stores/store-locator.html | title = Store Locator | publisher = Wegmans | accessdate = September 29, 2019|website = }}</ref> in the [[Mid-Atlantic states|mid-Atlantic]] and [[New England]] regions. The company has stores in [[New York (state)|New York]], [[Pennsylvania]], [[New Jersey]], [[Maryland]], [[Massachusetts]], [[Virginia]] and [[North Carolina]], with planned expansions into [[Delaware]]. Founded in 1916 in [[Rochester, New York|Rochester]], Wegmans has appeared on ''[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]''{{'}}s annual \"100 Best Companies to Work For\" list since the list first appeared in 1998.<ref name=\"Perry\">{{cite news|url=http://www.democratandchronicle.com/article/20090122/BUSINESS/90122013|title=Wegmans, Paychex make Fortune list of best employers|last=Perry|first=Kate|date=January 22, 2009|work=[[Democrat and Chronicle]]|accessdate=January 22, 2009}}{{Dead link|date=January 2010}}</ref> In 2020, the company was ranked at number three on their Fortune List of the Top 100 Companies to Work For in 2020 based on an employee survey of satisfaction.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/best-companies-to-work-for-based-on-employee-satisfaction-fortune-2020-2|title=The 25 best companies to work for, based on employee satisfaction|publisher=[[Business Insider]]|author=Jessica Snouwaert|accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref> \n\n==History==\nWegmans is a privately owned company, founded in 1916 by John and Walter Wegman as the '''Rochester Fruit and Vegetable Company'''.<ref name=\"wegmans.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wegmans.com/about-us/company-overview.html|title=Company Overview & History \u2013 Wegmans|publisher=Wegmans}}</ref> Wegmans is headquartered in the Rochester suburb of Gates. Danny Wegman is the chairman. His daughter, Colleen Wegman, is President and CEO; his other daughter, Nicole Wegman, is senior vice-president.<ref name=\"wegmans.com\"/> Danny's father, [[Robert Wegman]], who died in 2006, was previously chairman. Robert was the son of co-founder Walter Wegman. During his life, Robert Wegman was a pioneer in the retail food business, as well as a generous donor to educational institutions and other charities.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.storebrandsreviewed.com/blog/robert-wegman-innovation-and-integrity/|title=Robert Wegman: Innovation and Integrity|work=StoreBrandsReviewed|accessdate=March 27, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402140312/http://www.storebrandsreviewed.com/blog/robert-wegman-innovation-and-integrity/|archive-date=April 2, 2015|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=April 22, 2006 |work=[[The New York Times]] |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2006/04/22/business/22wegman.html |title=Robert Wegman, 87, Leader in Supermarket Innovations, Dies | agency=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref>\n\n===Expansion===\nIn 1965, the chain expanded beyond the Rochester area, with a store in Hornell in the Southern Tier of New York State, then 1968 in Syracuse,<ref name=\"weghist\">{{cite web|title=History|url=http://www.wegmans.com/webapp/wcs/stores/servlet/CategoryDisplay?categoryId=256611&storeId=10052&catalogId=10002&langId=-1|publisher=Wegmans|accessdate=January 1, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100108090409/http://www.wegmans.com/webapp/wcs/stores/servlet/CategoryDisplay?categoryId=256611&storeId=10052&catalogId=10002&langId=-1|archivedate=January 8, 2010|df=mdy-all}}</ref> and again in 1977 with its first Buffalo store.<ref name=\"weghist\"/> The first store outside New York opened in 1993 in Pennsylvania and the expansion continued into [[New Jersey]] in 1999,<ref name=\"weghist\"/> [[Virginia]] in 2004, and [[Maryland]] in 2005.<ref name=\"weghist\"/><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.wegmans.com/webapp/wcs/stores/servlet/CategoryDisplay?categoryId=281152&storeId=10052&catalogId=10002&langId=-1 |title= Wegmans Company Overview |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20151019022117/http://www.wegmans.com/webapp/wcs/stores/servlet/CategoryDisplay?categoryId=281152&storeId=10052&catalogId=10002&langId=-1 |archivedate= October 19, 2015 |df= mdy-all }}</ref> As a part of the company's continued expansion efforts, Wegmans opened its fifth Maryland location in [[Columbia, Maryland|Columbia]] on June 17, 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://baltimore.cbslocal.com/2012/06/17/new-wegmans-opens-in-columbia/|title=New Wegmans Opens in Columbia|author=|date=|publisher=|accessdate=November 29, 2016}}</ref> Its sixth Maryland location opened in [[Crofton, Maryland|Crofton]] on October 28, 2012, followed by a [[Germantown, Maryland|Germantown]] location on September 15, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newstores.wegmans.com/|title=Future Store Locations \u2013 Wegmans|author=|date=|publisher=|accessdate=November 29, 2016}}</ref> Wegmans opened a store at the [[Montgomery Mall (Pennsylvania)|Montgomery Mall]] in [[North Wales, Pennsylvania]], on November 3, 2013, the first store to be part of a shopping mall since the closing of the [[Midtown Plaza (Rochester, New York)|Midtown Plaza]] store in Rochester.<ref name=\"intell\">{{cite news|last=DeBree|first=Crissa Shoemaker|title=Wegmans' Montgomeryville store the chain's first at a mall|work=[[The Intelligencer (Doylestown, Pennsylvania)|The Intelligencer]]|date=November 17, 2011|accessdate=November 29, 2011|url=http://www.phillyburbs.com/news/local/money/wegmans-montgomeryville-store-the-chain-s-first-at-a-mall/article_323d46a0-d423-5e04-8640-fc274b0420d2.html|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111119015452/http://www.phillyburbs.com/news/local/money/wegmans-montgomeryville-store-the-chain-s-first-at-a-mall/article_323d46a0-d423-5e04-8640-fc274b0420d2.html|archivedate=November 19, 2011|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"reporter\">{{cite news|last=Connor|first=Jennifer|title=Montgomery Mall's Wegmans store opens big|work=[[The Reporter (Lansdale)|The Reporter]]|date=November 3, 2013|accessdate=November 5, 2013|url=http://www.thereporteronline.com/events/20131103/montgomery-malls-wegmans-store-opens-big}}</ref>\n\nWegmans, having long planned to expand into [[New England]],<ref name=\"mass1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.patriotledger.com/business/x1485832690/Westwood-OKs-liquor-license-for-proposed-Wegmans|title=Westwood OKs liquor license for proposed Wegmans|work=[[The Patriot Ledger]]|date=May 7, 2008|accessdate=January 4, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"mass2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.metrowestdailynews.com/news/x1198800850/The-Loop-in-Northborough-in-the-market-for-a-Wegmans|title=The Loop in Northborough in the market for a Wegmans|date=January 27, 2009|work=[[The MetroWest Daily News]]|author=Abby Jordan|accessdate=January 4, 2010}}</ref> opened their first store in that region in [[Northborough, Massachusetts]], on October 16, 2011.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.metrowestdailynews.com/news/x1876835107/Opening-of-Northborough-Wegmans-is-a-grand-affair|title= Opening of Northborough Wegmans is a grand affair|last1= Uek|first1= Kathy|last2= |first2= |date= October 17, 2011|work=[[The MetroWest Daily News]]|accessdate=October 19, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Bradley|first=Michelle|title=Wegmans Manager Humbled by Record-Breaking Opening|url=http://northborough.dailyvoice.com/news/wegmans-manager-humbled-record-breaking-opening|work=The Northborough Daily Voice|accessdate=July 26, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131013055222/http://northborough.dailyvoice.com/news/wegmans-manager-humbled-record-breaking-opening|archivedate=October 13, 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref> 2014 saw Wegmans opening two more Massachusetts stores, in [[Newton, Massachusetts|Newton]], Chestnut Hill on April 27,<ref>{{cite news|last=Rknepper|first=Rknepper|title=Chestnut Hill Wegmans Opens|url=http://www.boston.com/news/local/massachusetts/2014/04/26/hours-before-chestnut-hill-wegmans-opens/tVykzFvDYfKL7ONhw34cGM/story.html|accessdate=June 7, 2014|newspaper=Boston Globe|date=April 27, 2014}}</ref> and in [[Burlington, Massachusetts|Burlington]] on October 26.<ref>{{cite news|last=Abelson|first=Jen|title=Wegmans to build store near Burlington Mall|url=http://www.boston.com/business/articles/2011/06/04/wegmans_to_build_store_near_burlington_mall/|accessdate=June 7, 2011|newspaper=[[The Boston Globe]]|date=June 4, 2011}}</ref> Its fourth Massachusetts store opened in Westwood on October 11, 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Westwood falling in love with its new Wegmans|url = http://www.democratandchronicle.com/story/money/business/2015/10/14/westwood-falling-love-its-new-wegmans/73864308/|work = [[Democrat and Chronicle]]|accessdate = October 20, 2015}}</ref> The eighth Maryland store opened in [[Owings Mills, Maryland]] in September 2016.<ref name=\"Owings Mills Launch\">{{cite web|last1=Warren|first1=Pat|title=New Wegmans to Revitalize Owings Mills|url=http://baltimore.cbslocal.com/2016/09/16/new-wegmans-to-revitlaize-owings-mills/|publisher=CBS Baltimore|accessdate=September 26, 2016|ref=Owings Mills Launch}}</ref> In late 2016, Wegmans opened Virginia stores in [[Short Pump, Virginia|Short Pump]] (August),<ref name=\"va\"/> Midlothian,<ref name=\"va\">{{cite url|url=http://www.nbc12.com/story/31079699/wegmans-announces-opening-dates-for-midlothian-short-pump-stores?clienttype=generic|title=Wegmans announces opening dates for Midlothian, Short Pump stores|date=January 28, 2016|first=Ray|last=Daudani|accessdate=May 4, 2017}}</ref> and [[Charlottesville, Virginia|Charlottesville]] (November).<ref>{{cite url|url=http://www.richmondmagazine.com/restaurants-in-richmond/food-news/first-look-wegmans-short-pump/|accessdate=May 4, 2017|title=First Look: Wegmans Short Pump -Take a peek inside Short Pump's newest grocery store. Then take a \"micro stretch.\"|first=Stephanie|last=Breijo|work=Richmond Magazine|date=August 6, 2016}}</ref> The [[Hanover Township, New Jersey]] location opened in July 2017. The [[Montvale, New Jersey]] location opened in September 2017. The [[Medford, Massachusetts]] location opened on November 5, 2017.<ref>{{cite news| title = A massive Wegmans is opening in Medford | url = https://www.boston.com/news/local-news/2017/11/04/wegmans-medford-opening | work = [[The Boston Globe]] | first = Nik | last = DeCosta-Klipa\t| date = November 4, 2017 | accessdate = November 12, 2017}}</ref> The [[Natick, Massachusetts]] location opened on April 29, 2018. The [[Chantilly, Virginia]] location opened on June 3, 2018. The [[Lancaster, Pennsylvania]] location opened on September 23, 2018.<ref name=lnp>{{cite news|first=Tim|last=Mekeel |title=It's true: Wegmans is coming to Lancaster, picks site near Long's Park |url=http://lancasteronline.com/news/local/it-s-true-wegmans-is-coming-to-lancaster-picks-site/article_65005a9a-74db-11e5-ab5c-abbc223a93e1.html |work=[[LNP (newspaper)|LNP]]|date=October 18, 2015 |accessdate=February 13, 2016}}</ref> The [[Virginia Beach, Virginia]] location opened on April 28, 2019. The chain's first store in [[North Carolina]], located in [[Raleigh, North Carolina|Raleigh]], opened on September 29, 2019. It was also the chain's 100th store.<ref name=\"N&O\">[https://www.newsobserver.com/living/food-drink/article235608107.html '''''The News & Observer''''', ''The numbers are in: Raleigh breaks records in Wegmans store opening'', Ashad Hajela, September 30, 2019], Retrieved Dec. 23, 2019.</ref> The chain's first location in [[New York City]], at [[Admiral's Row]] in [[Brooklyn]]'s [[Brooklyn Navy Yard|Navy Yard]], opened on October 27, 2019.<ref>{{cite web | last=King | first=Kate | title=Wegmaniacs Count the Days to Brooklyn Store Opening | website=WSJ | date=October 13, 2019 | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/wegmaniacs-count-the-days-to-brooklyn-store-opening-11570978800 | access-date=October 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" align=\"right\"\n|+Number of Wegmans locations by state\n|-\n! State\n! {{abbr|No.|Number}}<br/>of locations\n|-\n| [[Massachusetts]]\n| 6\n|-\n| [[Maryland]]\n| 8\n|-\n| [[New Jersey]]\n| 9\n|-\n| [[New York (state)|New York]]\n| 47\n|-\n| [[North Carolina]]\n| 1\n|-\n| [[Pennsylvania]]\n| 18\n|-\n| [[Virginia]]\n| 12\n|}\n\nThe [[Harrison, New York]] location, in [[Westchester County, New York|Westchester County]], was originally scheduled to open on June 7, 2020, however, it was postponed to a date to be announced due to the coronavirus pandemic. The West Cary, North Carolina location is scheduled to open on August 2, 2020 and the [[Tysons Corner, Virginia]] location is scheduled to open in Fall 2020. Eleven other locations are currently in the works, including [[Middletown, New Jersey]]; four other locations in North Carolina, which are in [[Cary, North Carolina|Cary]], [[Chapel Hill, North Carolina|Chapel Hill]], [[Wake Forest, North Carolina|Wake Forest]] and [[Holly Springs, North Carolina|Holly Springs]]; [[Arcola, Virginia]]; a second Alexandria location in Carlyle; Washington, DC, in the Fannie Mae section; [[Rockville, Maryland]]; [[Reston, Virginia]]; [[Annapolis, Maryland]]; and [[Greenville, Delaware]], the chain's first location in that state.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wegmans.com/about-us/future-store-locations/|title=Future Store Locations|website=Wegmans|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.democratandchronicle.com/story/money/business/2016/08/02/wegmans-targets-north-carolina-expansion/87912886/|title=Wegmans targets North Carolina for expansion|author=|date=|publisher=|accessdate=November 29, 2016}}</ref><ref>[http://www.lohud.com/story/money/business/2016/12/14/wegmans-grocery-store-harrison/95440370/ Wegmans grocery store coming to Harrison] by Gabriel Rom, ''[[The Journal News]]'' December 14, 2016</ref><ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2015/05/13/nyregion/wegmans-to-open-at-brooklyn-navy-yard.html Wegmans to Open at Brooklyn Navy Yard] By MATT A.V. CHABAN, ''[[The New York Times]]'' May 12, 2015</ref><ref>[http://wavy.com/2017/01/19/wegmans-signs-lease-to-build-store-in-virginia-beach/ Wegmans signs lease to build new store in Virginia Beach] By Emily Satchell and Laura Caso for [[WAVY-TV]].com; January 19, 2017, 7:21&nbsp;pm</ref><ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/capital-business/wp/2017/05/21/wegmans-is-coming-to-washington/ Wegmans is coming to Washington] By Abha Bhattarai for ''[[The Washington Post]]'' May 21, 2017</ref><ref name=\"HOLLYSPRINGS\">[https://abc11.com/food/wegmans-planning-sixth-triangle-grocery-store-in-holly-springs/5148001/ WTVD Channel 11, ''Wegmans planning sixth Triangle grocery store in Holly Springs'' by Steven Daniels, February 21, 2019], Retrieved Oct. 6, 2019.</ref>\n\nIn March 2020, Wegmans announced partnership of its new Brooklyn store with [[Instacart]] to extend its reach to include all Manhattan ZIP codes.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.supermarketnews.com/online-retail/wegmans-brings-online-grocery-delivery-manhattan-instacart | title=Wegmans brings online grocery delivery to Manhattan via Instacart | first=Russell | last=Redman | work=[[Supermarket News]] | date=February 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Operations==\n[[File:Wegmans Woodmore storefront.jpg|thumb|300px|right|A modern Wegmans storefront circa 2010. This Wegmans is in [[Lanham, Maryland]] (a Washington, D.C. suburb) (referred to as the \"Woodmore\" store), the second Wegmans in Maryland]]\n[[File:Interior of Montvale Wegmans store.jpg|thumb|200px|right|The interior of the Wegmans store in [[Montvale, New Jersey]], 2017]]\n[[File:Wegmansmanalapan.jpg|thumb|right|300px|{{nowrap|A Wegmans store in [[Manalapan Township, New Jersey|Manalapan, New Jersey]]}} in 2009]]\n[[File:Wegmans footprint.png|thumb|200px|right|Map of Wegmans stores]]\n\nWegmans is ranked 29th on the ''[[Supermarket News]]'' list of the Top 75 North American Food Retailers based on sales volume,<ref name=\"2009SN\">{{cite web | url=https://www.supermarketnews.com/rankings-research/top-75-retailers-wholesalers | title=TOP 75 RETAILERS & WHOLESALERS | publisher=[[Supermarket News]]}}</ref> up from number 32 on the 2007 ''[[Supermarket News]]'' list,<ref name=\"2007 SN\" /> and 7th among privately held U.S. supermarkets.{{Citation needed|date=December 2007}} In 2009 ''Stores Magazine'' showed it to be the 74th-largest retailer in the United States with estimated revenues of $4.67&nbsp;billion.<ref name=\"stores09\">{{cite web |url=http://www.stores.org/pdf/09Top100chart.pdf|title=Stores Top 100 Retailers|date=July 2009|publisher=Stores.org|accessdate=January 5, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090807014920/http://www.stores.org/pdf/09Top100Chart.pdf|archive-date=August 7, 2009|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> As of 2006, it was the 66th largest privately held company, as determined by ''[[Forbes]]''.<ref name=\"forbes06\">{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/lists/2006/21/biz_06privates_Wegmans-Food-Markets_MGF0.html|work=Forbes|title=#66 Wegmans Food Markets|date=November 9, 2006|accessdate=January 5, 2010}}</ref> On Forbes's 2005 list, Wegmans ranked 54th.<ref>{{cite journal | magazine=Forbes | title=America's Largest Private Companies | url=https://www.forbes.com/2005/11/09/largest-private-companies_05private_land.html| date=November 11, 2005 | accessdate=November 16, 2006}}</ref>\n\nMost of Wegmans' newer stores are of the [[superstore]] or megamarket type, with a large area, a variety of foods aimed at an upscale [[clientele]], and, in many stores, Market Caf\u00e9 in-store dining areas. From 2002\u20132009, Wegmans owned and operated Tastings, a full-service restaurant at its [[Pittsford (town), New York|Pittsford, New York]] store.<ref name=\"wegmans.com\"/> Tastings was replaced with The Food Bar, a \"seafood shack\"-styled restaurant in the same space; and later with The Burger Bar, serving hamburgers. Next Door by Wegmans, a stand-alone restaurant operated by Wegmans, opened across the street from the Pittsford store in 2009.\n\nIn January 2007, Wegmans announced two business ventures: (1) opening a {{convert|19000|sqft|m2|-2|abbr=on}} liquor store in Pittsford (adding to its two existing wine centers, in Virginia and New Jersey); and (2) the creation of a $28&nbsp;million Culinary Innovation Center in [[Chili, New York]], a corporate research and development facility, including a new central kitchen, replacing some of the operations at its meat center.<ref>{{cite news | last = Rand | first = Ben | title = Wegmans embarks on 2 local projects | work = [[Democrat and Chronicle]]| date = January 6, 2007| url = http://www.democratandchronicle.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20070106/BUSINESS/701060306 | accessdate =January 6, 2007}}{{Dead link|date=January 2010}}</ref> The liquor store opened in April 2008 as Century Pittsford Wines. The store is {{convert|45000|sqft|m2|-2|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pittsfordplaza.com/News/Article.aspx?id=176 |title=Pittsford Plaza \u2013 Century Pittsford Wines run independently of Wegmans |accessdate=June 13, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080616041125/http://www.pittsfordplaza.com/News/Article.aspx?id=176 |archivedate=June 16, 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.allbusiness.com/retail-trade/food-stores/4478555-1.html |title= Rundown of New York State liquor laws prohibiting wine and liquor sales in grocery stores|accessdate=June 13, 2008}}</ref> This business model has been replicated at three other New York Wegmans locations, in Buffalo, DeWitt and Johnson City. Ownership of each liquor store is held by a different member of the Wegman family due to New York State regulations prohibiting individuals or corporations from owning multiple liquor stores.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.buffalonews.com/city-region/north-buffalo-hertel/opening-soon-in-wegmans-parking-lot-amherst-st-wine-liquor-20141017 |title= Opening soon in Wegmans parking lot: Amherst St. Wine & Liquor}}</ref>\n\nAfter Wegmans updated their logo to a script font, in November 2010, [[Walgreens]] filed a [[trademark infringement]] [[lawsuit]] against Wegmans, claiming the \"W\" in the Wegman's logo was too similar to Walgreens.<ref>{{cite news|title=Walgreens sues Wegmans in logo dispute |newspaper=The Wall Street Journal |date=November 6, 2010 |url=http://online.wsj.com/article/AP0d26cbf8d065497781f4dc5f4336a3b3.html |accessdate=November 17, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101108222151/http://online.wsj.com/article/AP0d26cbf8d065497781f4dc5f4336a3b3.html |archivedate=November 8, 2010 }}</ref> The lawsuit was settled in April 2011, with Wegmans agreeing to discontinue use of its \"W\" logo by June 2012, although the supermarket retains the right to use the \"Wegmans\" name in script.<ref name=\"auipb\">{{cite web |url= http://www.ipbrief.net/2011/04/27/wegmans-settles-with-walgreens-over-war-of-w%E2%80%99s/|title= Wegmans Settles with Walgreens over War of W's|author= Richard Patterson|date= April 27, 2011|work= Intellectual Property Brief|publisher= American University|accessdate=June 9, 2011}}</ref> According to Jo Natale, Wegmans director of media relations, \"The cost of making relatively minor changes to a limited number of products was much less than the cost of litigating this case to the end.\"<ref name=\"walgreenpr\">{{cite web|url= http://www.wegmans.com/webapp/wcs/stores/servlet/PressReleaseDetailView?langId=-1&storeId=10052&catalogId=10002&productId=720935|title= Press Release: Wegmans Releases Statement on Lawsuit Resolution|accessdate= June 9, 2011|url-status= dead|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110505055539/http://www.wegmans.com/webapp/wcs/stores/servlet/PressReleaseDetailView?productId=720935&storeId=10052&catalogId=10002&langId=-1|archivedate= May 5, 2011|df= mdy-all}}</ref>\n[[File:Wegmans exterior.jpg|right|200px|thumb|Exterior of a Wegmans store in [[Amherst, New York]], known as the \"Alberta Drive\" location, in 2006, in the style common in the late 1990s]]\nWegmans offers a pick-up service called \"Personal Shopping\" at select locations.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web |url=https://www.wegmans.com/service/personal-shopping.html |title=Personal Shopping |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=2017 |publisher=Wegmans |access-date=January 25, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202074540/https://www.wegmans.com/service/personal-shopping.html |archive-date=February 2, 2017 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> In June 2017, Wegmans partnered with [[Instacart]] to provide home delivery service.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.recode.net/2017/6/14/15793304/wegmans-delivery-instacart-groceries-washington-dc-virginia-maryland |title=The Wegmans grocery chain is introducing delivery in partnership with Instacart |author= Jason Del Rey |date=June 14, 2017 |work=[[Recode]] |access-date=September 19, 2017 |quote=}}</ref>\n\nOn January 30, 2016, Wegmans celebrated its 100th anniversary.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Wegmans celebrates 100 years in business|url = http://www.democratandchronicle.com/story/news/2016/01/30/wegmans-celebrates-100-years-business/79511060/|work = [[Democrat and Chronicle]] |access-date = January 31, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, Wegmans announced its [[Brooklyn]] store would offer grocery delivery to [[Manhattan]] residents, an expansion on their [[Instacart]] partnership. Delivery fees start at $3.99, and Manhattan customers are given a two to five hour delivery window. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://progressivegrocer.com/wegmans-brooklyn-store-offers-grocery-delivery-manhattan|title=Wegmans\u2019 Brooklyn Store Offers Grocery Delivery to Manhattan|website=Progressive Grocer|language=en|access-date=2020-02-19}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2020, in response to the Covid-19 outbreak, wegmans began limiting the number people in their stores, provided their employees with masks and installed plexiglass shields at all checkout areas<ref>https://www.syracuse.com/coronavirus/2020/04/wegmans-limiting-shoppers-in-stores-starting-employee-temperature-checks.html</ref>\n\n==Accolades and fanbase==\nWegmans has received much media attention for customer fan base, organic food, [[Salad bar|hot food bar]], the depth of its food selection and employee happiness.<ref>[http://www.pymnts.com/news/retail/2017/the-wonder-of-wegmans-2/ The Wonder Of Wegmans] by PYMNTS.com Posted on January 9, 2017</ref> [[Food Network]] recognized it with its award for Best Grocery Store in 2007.<ref>{{cite press release | title = And the Winner is Wegmans! | publisher = Wegmans | date = April 16, 2007 | url = https://www.wegmans.com/webapp/wcs/stores/servlet/PressReleaseDetailView?langId=-1&storeId=10052&catalogId=10002&productId=399613 | accessdate = October 22, 2008 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110724032925/https://www.wegmans.com/webapp/wcs/stores/servlet/PressReleaseDetailView?langId=-1&storeId=10052&catalogId=10002&productId=399613 | archivedate = July 24, 2011 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> ''[[Consumer Reports]]'' subscribers voted Wegmans the top grocery store in 2017; it has held the top spot since 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.democratandchronicle.com/story/money/business/2017/05/30/consumer-reports-subscribers-again-rank-wegmans-no-1/356210001/|title='Consumer Reports' subscribers pick Wegmans as top grocer, again|publisher=}}</ref> It was also profiled as part of the \"Here Are The Jobs\" segment on [[MSNBC]]'s ''[[PoliticsNation]]'' on July 6, 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/46044226 |title='Here are the jobs' |publisher=NBC News }}</ref> In 2016, Market Force surveyed over 10,000 grocery store shoppers nationwide, and Wegmans was rated \"America's favorite grocery store\".<ref>[http://money.cnn.com/2016/04/20/pf/americas-favorite-grocery-store/  America's favorite grocery store is...] by Kathryn Vasel for CNN; April 20, 2016</ref>\n\nWegmans has a loyal fan base of customers who have received recognition for their devotion, who have lined up overnight in the thousands for a new store opening, regularly write \"[[love letter]]s\" to the store to ask for one to open in a region not presently served, and in [[Northborough, Massachusetts]], many high school students staged a musical about the store.<ref>[http://www.adweek.com/brand-marketing/why-do-so-many-people-go-crazy-wegmans-169396/ Why Do So Many People Go Crazy for Wegmans? \u2013 How an upstate New York grocer found a national cult following] By Robert Klara; February 12, 2016</ref><ref>[https://www.thrillist.com/eat/nation/wegmans-grocery-stores-super-fans HOW WEGMANS INSPIRED THE MOST RABID FANBASE IN THE GROCERY WORLD] By PRIYA KRISHNA for [[Thrillist Media Group]] Published on October 2, 2017</ref> The store's fans have their own Twitter [[hashtag]] \"[https://twitter.com/search?f=tweets&vertical=default&q=wegmania #Wegmania]\" and a Tumblr.\n\n==Chase-Pitkin Home and Garden Centers==\nWegmans was the parent company of Chase-Pitkin, a regional [[home improvement]] retailer. On October 4, 2005, Wegmans announced that it would close all Chase-Pitkin stores by early 2006<ref name=\"aubpub\">{{cite web |url=http://www.auburnpub.com/news/local/article_a80b2670-7696-52bf-8f1b-c30970206dcd.html?mode=story|title= Wegmans to close all Chase-Pitkins |date= October 5, 2005|publisher= auburnpub.com|accessdate=January 4, 2010}}</ref> and focus on its supermarket operations. The decision to exit the home improvement business was reportedly due to the increasing dominance of national chains such as [[Lowe's]] and [[The Home Depot]].<ref name=\"aubpub\"/> Chase-Pitkin stores closed individually at various points throughout March 2006.{{citation needed|date=November 2017}}\n\n==Discontinuation of tobacco products==\nIn January 2008, Wegmans announced that it would no longer sell tobacco products because of their negative effects on human health and the environment<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/baltimore/stories/2007/12/31/daily30.html|title=Wegmans ceasing tobacco sales|publisher=Baltimore Business Journal|author=James Fink|date=January 4, 2008|accessdate=January 4, 2010}}</ref> and would offer smoking cessation programs to all employees.<ref name=\"conaff1\">{{cite web|title=Wegmans, DeCicco Markets Ditch Cigarettes|url=http://www.consumeraffairs.com/news04/2008/06/stores_tobacco.html|publisher=consumeraffairs.com|date=June 2, 2008|accessdate=January 4, 2010}}</ref> The decision drew praise from the [[American Lung Association]] of New York State, which presented Wegmans with the \"Lung Champion Award\".<ref name=\"conaff1\"/>\n\n==Wegmans brand==\nWegmans began branding some products in 1979, offering basic commodities at a lower price than national brands. The Wegmans brand has gradually expanded. In 1992, it began a line of healthy products, Food You Feel Good About. Wegmans brand products marked with the Food You Feel Good About banner indicate that the product does not contain artificial colors, flavors, or preservatives. The next sub-brand to be launched was Italian Classics, in 1995; it introduced pastas, canned tomatoes, and olive oils imported from Italy. In 2002, Wegmans launched a line of organic products. Organic Wegmans brand products are labeled with a green leaf.\n\n==In popular culture==\nThe Wegmans brand was used extensively in the American sitcom ''[[The Office (U.S. TV series)|The Office]]''. The program is set in the city of [[Scranton, Pennsylvania]], which has a Wegmans store, although the series was filmed in suburban Los Angeles.<ref>{{cite news | first = Christine Carrie | last = Fien | title =  TV SCENE: Wegmans checks in at 'The Office' | url = http://www.rochestercitynewspaper.com/news/articles/TV+SCENE:+Wegmans+checks+in+at++The+Office+/ | work = [[City Newspaper]] | date = March 7, 2007 | accessdate =April 12, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.wegmans.com/webapp/wcs/stores/servlet/StoreDetailView?langId=-1&storeId=10052&catalogId=10002&productId=347976 | title = Wegmans Locator Detail for Scranton, PA | publisher = Wegmans | accessdate = April 12, 2008 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080612201458/http://www.wegmans.com/webapp/wcs/stores/servlet/StoreDetailView?langId=-1&storeId=10052&catalogId=10002&productId=347976 | archivedate = June 12, 2008 | df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nWegman's Bake and Rise Four Cheese Frozen Pizza has been reviewed on Barstool Sports' One Bite Pizza Reviews by David Portnoy. The score for the frozen pizza was an 8.1. Per, Portnoy this score is on the frozen pizza scale and does not translate to an 8.1 on the normal pizza place scale score. However, as of April 9th, 2020, this is the highest score Portnoy has given to a frozen pizza.<ref>https://www.barstoolsports.com/video/2257799/barstool-frozen-pizza-review-wegmans-pizza</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* ''Wegmans footprint in Pennsylvania'' ~ {{cite news | url=http://www.bizjournals.com/philadelphia/blog/real-estate/2014/07/wegmans-leases-land-in-chadds-ford-plans-140-000.html | title=Wegmans leases land in Chadds Ford, plans 140,000-square-foot store | work=[[Phila. Bus. J.]] | date=July 25, 2014 | author=Kostelni, Natalie }}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|New York (state)|Companies|Food}}\n* {{official website|https://www.wegmans.com/}}\n\n{{Supermarkets of the United States}}\n{{City of Rochester, NY}}\n\n[[Category:Economy of the Northeastern United States]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Rochester, New York]]\n[[Category:Privately held companies based in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Retail companies established in 1916]]\n[[Category:Supermarkets of the United States]]\n[[Category:1916 establishments in New York (state)]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Supermarket chain in the northeastern United States}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2017}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Wegmans Food Markets, Inc.\n| logo = File:WegmansLogo.svg\n| logo_size = 250px\n| image = Wegmans in Lancaster PA.jpg\n| image_size = 250px\n| image_caption = The exterior of a typical Wegmans, pictured in 2018 in Lancaster, Pennsylvania.\n| former_name = Rochester Fruit and Vegetable Company (1916-1930)\n| type = {{flat list|\n* Private\n* [[family business]]\n}}\n| industry = [[Grocery|Retail (Grocery)]]\n| founder = {{plain list|\n* John Wegman\n* Walter Wegman\n}}\n| founded = {{start date and age|1916}} in [[Rochester, New York]], U.S.\n| location_city = [[Rochester, New York]]\n| location_country = U.S.\n| num_locations = 101<ref name=\"StoreLocator\"/>\n| num_locations_year = \n| area_served = {{flat list|\n* [[Maryland]]\n* [[Massachusetts]]\n* [[New Jersey]]\n* [[New York (state)|New York]]\n* [[Pennsylvania]]\n* [[Virginia]]\n* [[North Carolina]]\n}}\n| key_people = {{plain list|\n* Colleen J. Wegman (president and CEO)\n* Nicole Wegman (Sr. Vice President)\n* Danny Wegman (chairman)\n}}\n| revenue = {{profit}} $9.2&nbsp;billion (2018)<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/companies/wegmans-food-markets/|title=Wegmans Food Markets on the Forbes Best Employers for Diversity List|work=Forbes|access-date=2018-04-28|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"hoovers\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hoovers.com/company/Wegmans_Food_Markets_Inc/cfhtji-1.html|title=!company_name! \u2013 Company Profile from Hoover's|author=|date=|publisher=|accessdate=November 29, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"2007 SN\">{{cite web|url=http://www.supermarketnews.com/sns-top-75/|title=SN's Top 75|author=|date=|publisher=|accessdate=November 29, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"wegmans\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wegmans.com/webapp/wcs/stores/servlet/CategoryDisplay?categoryId=281152&storeId=10052&catalogId=10002&langId=-1|title=Home \u2013 Wegmans|accessdate=November 29, 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151019022117/http://www.wegmans.com/webapp/wcs/stores/servlet/CategoryDisplay?categoryId=281152&storeId=10052&catalogId=10002&langId=-1|archivedate=October 19, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n| owner         = Wegman Enterprises, Inc (Wegman family (100%))\n| num_employees = 49,000\n| num_employees_year = \n| homepage = {{URL|wegmans.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Wegmans Food Markets, Inc.''' is a [[privately held company|privately held]] American [[supermarket]] chain; it is headquartered in [[Rochester, New York|Rochester]], [[New York (state)|New York]]. As of October 2019, Wegmans has 101 stores<ref name=\"StoreLocator\">{{cite web| url = https://www.wegmans.com/stores/store-locator.html | title = Store Locator | publisher = Wegmans | accessdate = September 29, 2019|website = }}</ref> in the [[Mid-Atlantic states|mid-Atlantic]] and [[New England]] regions. The company has stores in [[New York (state)|New York]], [[Pennsylvania]], [[New Jersey]], [[Maryland]], [[Massachusetts]], [[Virginia]] and [[North Carolina]], with planned expansions into [[Delaware]]. Founded in 1916 in [[Rochester, New York|Rochester]], Wegmans has appeared on ''[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]''{{'}}s annual \"100 Best Companies to Work For\" list since the list first appeared in 1998.<ref name=\"Perry\">{{cite news|url=http://www.democratandchronicle.com/article/20090122/BUSINESS/90122013|title=Wegmans, Paychex make Fortune list of best employers|last=Perry|first=Kate|date=January 22, 2009|work=[[Democrat and Chronicle]]|accessdate=January 22, 2009}}{{Dead link|date=January 2010}}</ref> In 2020, the company was ranked at number three on their Fortune List of the Top 100 Companies to Work For in 2020 based on an employee survey of satisfaction.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/best-companies-to-work-for-based-on-employee-satisfaction-fortune-2020-2|title=The 25 best companies to work for, based on employee satisfaction|publisher=[[Business Insider]]|author=Jessica Snouwaert|accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref> \n\n==History==\nWegmans is a privately owned company, founded in 1916 by John and Walter Wegman as the '''Rochester Fruit and Vegetable Company'''.<ref name=\"wegmans.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wegmans.com/about-us/company-overview.html|title=Company Overview & History \u2013 Wegmans|publisher=Wegmans}}</ref> Wegmans is headquartered in the Rochester suburb of Gates. Danny Wegman is the chairman. His daughter, Colleen Wegman, is President and CEO; his other daughter, Nicole Wegman, is senior vice-president.<ref name=\"wegmans.com\"/> Danny's father, [[Robert Wegman]], who died in 2006, was previously chairman. Robert was the son of co-founder Walter Wegman. During his life, Robert Wegman was a pioneer in the retail food business, as well as a generous donor to educational institutions and other charities.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.storebrandsreviewed.com/blog/robert-wegman-innovation-and-integrity/|title=Robert Wegman: Innovation and Integrity|work=StoreBrandsReviewed|accessdate=March 27, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402140312/http://www.storebrandsreviewed.com/blog/robert-wegman-innovation-and-integrity/|archive-date=April 2, 2015|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=April 22, 2006 |work=[[The New York Times]] |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2006/04/22/business/22wegman.html |title=Robert Wegman, 87, Leader in Supermarket Innovations, Dies | agency=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref>\n\n===Expansion===\nIn 1965, the chain expanded beyond the Rochester area, with a store in Hornell in the Southern Tier of New York State, then 1968 in Syracuse,<ref name=\"weghist\">{{cite web|title=History|url=http://www.wegmans.com/webapp/wcs/stores/servlet/CategoryDisplay?categoryId=256611&storeId=10052&catalogId=10002&langId=-1|publisher=Wegmans|accessdate=January 1, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100108090409/http://www.wegmans.com/webapp/wcs/stores/servlet/CategoryDisplay?categoryId=256611&storeId=10052&catalogId=10002&langId=-1|archivedate=January 8, 2010|df=mdy-all}}</ref> and again in 1977 with its first Buffalo store.<ref name=\"weghist\"/> The first store outside New York opened in 1993 in Pennsylvania and the expansion continued into [[New Jersey]] in 1999,<ref name=\"weghist\"/> [[Virginia]] in 2004, and [[Maryland]] in 2005.<ref name=\"weghist\"/><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.wegmans.com/webapp/wcs/stores/servlet/CategoryDisplay?categoryId=281152&storeId=10052&catalogId=10002&langId=-1 |title= Wegmans Company Overview |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20151019022117/http://www.wegmans.com/webapp/wcs/stores/servlet/CategoryDisplay?categoryId=281152&storeId=10052&catalogId=10002&langId=-1 |archivedate= October 19, 2015 |df= mdy-all }}</ref> As a part of the company's continued expansion efforts, Wegmans opened its fifth Maryland location in [[Columbia, Maryland|Columbia]] on June 17, 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://baltimore.cbslocal.com/2012/06/17/new-wegmans-opens-in-columbia/|title=New Wegmans Opens in Columbia|author=|date=|publisher=|accessdate=November 29, 2016}}</ref> Its sixth Maryland location opened in [[Crofton, Maryland|Crofton]] on October 28, 2012, followed by a [[Germantown, Maryland|Germantown]] location on September 15, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newstores.wegmans.com/|title=Future Store Locations \u2013 Wegmans|author=|date=|publisher=|accessdate=November 29, 2016}}</ref> Wegmans opened a store at the [[Montgomery Mall (Pennsylvania)|Montgomery Mall]] in [[North Wales, Pennsylvania]], on November 3, 2013, the first store to be part of a shopping mall since the closing of the [[Midtown Plaza (Rochester, New York)|Midtown Plaza]] store in Rochester.<ref name=\"intell\">{{cite news|last=DeBree|first=Crissa Shoemaker|title=Wegmans' Montgomeryville store the chain's first at a mall|work=[[The Intelligencer (Doylestown, Pennsylvania)|The Intelligencer]]|date=November 17, 2011|accessdate=November 29, 2011|url=http://www.phillyburbs.com/news/local/money/wegmans-montgomeryville-store-the-chain-s-first-at-a-mall/article_323d46a0-d423-5e04-8640-fc274b0420d2.html|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111119015452/http://www.phillyburbs.com/news/local/money/wegmans-montgomeryville-store-the-chain-s-first-at-a-mall/article_323d46a0-d423-5e04-8640-fc274b0420d2.html|archivedate=November 19, 2011|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"reporter\">{{cite news|last=Connor|first=Jennifer|title=Montgomery Mall's Wegmans store opens big|work=[[The Reporter (Lansdale)|The Reporter]]|date=November 3, 2013|accessdate=November 5, 2013|url=http://www.thereporteronline.com/events/20131103/montgomery-malls-wegmans-store-opens-big}}</ref>\n\nWegmans, having long planned to expand into [[New England]],<ref name=\"mass1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.patriotledger.com/business/x1485832690/Westwood-OKs-liquor-license-for-proposed-Wegmans|title=Westwood OKs liquor license for proposed Wegmans|work=[[The Patriot Ledger]]|date=May 7, 2008|accessdate=January 4, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"mass2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.metrowestdailynews.com/news/x1198800850/The-Loop-in-Northborough-in-the-market-for-a-Wegmans|title=The Loop in Northborough in the market for a Wegmans|date=January 27, 2009|work=[[The MetroWest Daily News]]|author=Abby Jordan|accessdate=January 4, 2010}}</ref> opened their first store in that region in [[Northborough, Massachusetts]], on October 16, 2011.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.metrowestdailynews.com/news/x1876835107/Opening-of-Northborough-Wegmans-is-a-grand-affair|title= Opening of Northborough Wegmans is a grand affair|last1= Uek|first1= Kathy|last2= |first2= |date= October 17, 2011|work=[[The MetroWest Daily News]]|accessdate=October 19, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Bradley|first=Michelle|title=Wegmans Manager Humbled by Record-Breaking Opening|url=http://northborough.dailyvoice.com/news/wegmans-manager-humbled-record-breaking-opening|work=The Northborough Daily Voice|accessdate=July 26, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131013055222/http://northborough.dailyvoice.com/news/wegmans-manager-humbled-record-breaking-opening|archivedate=October 13, 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref> 2014 saw Wegmans opening two more Massachusetts stores, in [[Newton, Massachusetts|Newton]], Chestnut Hill on April 27,<ref>{{cite news|last=Rknepper|first=Rknepper|title=Chestnut Hill Wegmans Opens|url=http://www.boston.com/news/local/massachusetts/2014/04/26/hours-before-chestnut-hill-wegmans-opens/tVykzFvDYfKL7ONhw34cGM/story.html|accessdate=June 7, 2014|newspaper=Boston Globe|date=April 27, 2014}}</ref> and in [[Burlington, Massachusetts|Burlington]] on October 26.<ref>{{cite news|last=Abelson|first=Jen|title=Wegmans to build store near Burlington Mall|url=http://www.boston.com/business/articles/2011/06/04/wegmans_to_build_store_near_burlington_mall/|accessdate=June 7, 2011|newspaper=[[The Boston Globe]]|date=June 4, 2011}}</ref> Its fourth Massachusetts store opened in Westwood on October 11, 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Westwood falling in love with its new Wegmans|url = http://www.democratandchronicle.com/story/money/business/2015/10/14/westwood-falling-love-its-new-wegmans/73864308/|work = [[Democrat and Chronicle]]|accessdate = October 20, 2015}}</ref> The eighth Maryland store opened in [[Owings Mills, Maryland]] in September 2016.<ref name=\"Owings Mills Launch\">{{cite web|last1=Warren|first1=Pat|title=New Wegmans to Revitalize Owings Mills|url=http://baltimore.cbslocal.com/2016/09/16/new-wegmans-to-revitlaize-owings-mills/|publisher=CBS Baltimore|accessdate=September 26, 2016|ref=Owings Mills Launch}}</ref> In late 2016, Wegmans opened Virginia stores in [[Short Pump, Virginia|Short Pump]] (August),<ref name=\"va\"/> Midlothian,<ref name=\"va\">{{cite url|url=http://www.nbc12.com/story/31079699/wegmans-announces-opening-dates-for-midlothian-short-pump-stores?clienttype=generic|title=Wegmans announces opening dates for Midlothian, Short Pump stores|date=January 28, 2016|first=Ray|last=Daudani|accessdate=May 4, 2017}}</ref> and [[Charlottesville, Virginia|Charlottesville]] (November).<ref>{{cite url|url=http://www.richmondmagazine.com/restaurants-in-richmond/food-news/first-look-wegmans-short-pump/|accessdate=May 4, 2017|title=First Look: Wegmans Short Pump -Take a peek inside Short Pump's newest grocery store. Then take a \"micro stretch.\"|first=Stephanie|last=Breijo|work=Richmond Magazine|date=August 6, 2016}}</ref> The [[Hanover Township, New Jersey]] location opened in July 2017. The [[Montvale, New Jersey]] location opened in September 2017. The [[Medford, Massachusetts]] location opened on November 5, 2017.<ref>{{cite news| title = A massive Wegmans is opening in Medford | url = https://www.boston.com/news/local-news/2017/11/04/wegmans-medford-opening | work = [[The Boston Globe]] | first = Nik | last = DeCosta-Klipa\t| date = November 4, 2017 | accessdate = November 12, 2017}}</ref> The [[Natick, Massachusetts]] location opened on April 29, 2018. The [[Chantilly, Virginia]] location opened on June 3, 2018. The [[Lancaster, Pennsylvania]] location opened on September 23, 2018.<ref name=lnp>{{cite news|first=Tim|last=Mekeel |title=It's true: Wegmans is coming to Lancaster, picks site near Long's Park |url=http://lancasteronline.com/news/local/it-s-true-wegmans-is-coming-to-lancaster-picks-site/article_65005a9a-74db-11e5-ab5c-abbc223a93e1.html |work=[[LNP (newspaper)|LNP]]|date=October 18, 2015 |accessdate=February 13, 2016}}</ref> The [[Virginia Beach, Virginia]] location opened on April 28, 2019. The chain's first store in [[North Carolina]], located in [[Raleigh, North Carolina|Raleigh]], opened on September 29, 2019. It was also the chain's 100th store.<ref name=\"N&O\">[https://www.newsobserver.com/living/food-drink/article235608107.html '''''The News & Observer''''', ''The numbers are in: Raleigh breaks records in Wegmans store opening'', Ashad Hajela, September 30, 2019], Retrieved Dec. 23, 2019.</ref> The chain's first location in [[New York City]], at [[Admiral's Row]] in [[Brooklyn]]'s [[Brooklyn Navy Yard|Navy Yard]], opened on October 27, 2019.<ref>{{cite web | last=King | first=Kate | title=Wegmaniacs Count the Days to Brooklyn Store Opening | website=WSJ | date=October 13, 2019 | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/wegmaniacs-count-the-days-to-brooklyn-store-opening-11570978800 | access-date=October 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" align=\"right\"\n|+Number of Wegmans locations by state\n|-\n! State\n! {{abbr|No.|Number}}<br/>of locations\n|-\n| [[Massachusetts]]\n| 6\n|-\n| [[Maryland]]\n| 8\n|-\n| [[New Jersey]]\n| 9\n|-\n| [[New York (state)|New York]]\n| 47\n|-\n| [[North Carolina]]\n| 1\n|-\n| [[Pennsylvania]]\n| 18\n|-\n| [[Virginia]]\n| 12\n|}\n\nThe [[Harrison, New York]] location, in [[Westchester County, New York|Westchester County]], was originally scheduled to open on June 7, 2020, however, it was postponed to a date to be announced due to the coronavirus pandemic. The West Cary, North Carolina location is scheduled to open on August 2, 2020 and the [[Tysons Corner, Virginia]] location is scheduled to open in Fall 2020. Eleven other locations are currently in the works, including [[Middletown, New Jersey]]; four other locations in North Carolina, which are in [[Cary, North Carolina|Cary]], [[Chapel Hill, North Carolina|Chapel Hill]], [[Wake Forest, North Carolina|Wake Forest]] and [[Holly Springs, North Carolina|Holly Springs]]; [[Arcola, Virginia]]; a second Alexandria location in Carlyle; Washington, DC, in the Fannie Mae section; [[Rockville, Maryland]]; [[Reston, Virginia]]; [[Annapolis, Maryland]]; and [[Greenville, Delaware]], the chain's first location in that state.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wegmans.com/about-us/future-store-locations/|title=Future Store Locations|website=Wegmans|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.democratandchronicle.com/story/money/business/2016/08/02/wegmans-targets-north-carolina-expansion/87912886/|title=Wegmans targets North Carolina for expansion|author=|date=|publisher=|accessdate=November 29, 2016}}</ref><ref>[http://www.lohud.com/story/money/business/2016/12/14/wegmans-grocery-store-harrison/95440370/ Wegmans grocery store coming to Harrison] by Gabriel Rom, ''[[The Journal News]]'' December 14, 2016</ref><ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2015/05/13/nyregion/wegmans-to-open-at-brooklyn-navy-yard.html Wegmans to Open at Brooklyn Navy Yard] By MATT A.V. CHABAN, ''[[The New York Times]]'' May 12, 2015</ref><ref>[http://wavy.com/2017/01/19/wegmans-signs-lease-to-build-store-in-virginia-beach/ Wegmans signs lease to build new store in Virginia Beach] By Emily Satchell and Laura Caso for [[WAVY-TV]].com; January 19, 2017, 7:21&nbsp;pm</ref><ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/capital-business/wp/2017/05/21/wegmans-is-coming-to-washington/ Wegmans is coming to Washington] By Abha Bhattarai for ''[[The Washington Post]]'' May 21, 2017</ref><ref name=\"HOLLYSPRINGS\">[https://abc11.com/food/wegmans-planning-sixth-triangle-grocery-store-in-holly-springs/5148001/ WTVD Channel 11, ''Wegmans planning sixth Triangle grocery store in Holly Springs'' by Steven Daniels, February 21, 2019], Retrieved Oct. 6, 2019.</ref>\n\nIn March 2020, Wegmans announced partnership of its new Brooklyn store with [[Instacart]] to extend its reach to include all Manhattan ZIP codes.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.supermarketnews.com/online-retail/wegmans-brings-online-grocery-delivery-manhattan-instacart | title=Wegmans brings online grocery delivery to Manhattan via Instacart | first=Russell | last=Redman | work=[[Supermarket News]] | date=February 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Operations==\n[[File:Wegmans Woodmore storefront.jpg|thumb|300px|right|A modern Wegmans storefront circa 2010. This Wegmans is in [[Lanham, Maryland]] (a Washington, D.C. suburb) (referred to as the \"Woodmore\" store), the second Wegmans in Maryland]]\n[[File:Interior of Montvale Wegmans store.jpg|thumb|200px|right|The interior of the Wegmans store in [[Montvale, New Jersey]], 2017]]\n[[File:Wegmansmanalapan.jpg|thumb|right|300px|{{nowrap|A Wegmans store in [[Manalapan Township, New Jersey|Manalapan, New Jersey]]}} in 2009]]\n[[File:Wegmans footprint.png|thumb|200px|right|Map of Wegmans stores]]\n\nWegmans is ranked 29th on the ''[[Supermarket News]]'' list of the Top 75 North American Food Retailers based on sales volume,<ref name=\"2009SN\">{{cite web | url=https://www.supermarketnews.com/rankings-research/top-75-retailers-wholesalers | title=TOP 75 RETAILERS & WHOLESALERS | publisher=[[Supermarket News]]}}</ref> up from number 32 on the 2007 ''[[Supermarket News]]'' list,<ref name=\"2007 SN\" /> and 7th among privately held U.S. supermarkets.{{Citation needed|date=December 2007}} In 2009 ''Stores Magazine'' showed it to be the 74th-largest retailer in the United States with estimated revenues of $4.67&nbsp;billion.<ref name=\"stores09\">{{cite web |url=http://www.stores.org/pdf/09Top100chart.pdf|title=Stores Top 100 Retailers|date=July 2009|publisher=Stores.org|accessdate=January 5, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090807014920/http://www.stores.org/pdf/09Top100Chart.pdf|archive-date=August 7, 2009|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> As of 2006, it was the 66th largest privately held company, as determined by ''[[Forbes]]''.<ref name=\"forbes06\">{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/lists/2006/21/biz_06privates_Wegmans-Food-Markets_MGF0.html|work=Forbes|title=#66 Wegmans Food Markets|date=November 9, 2006|accessdate=January 5, 2010}}</ref> On Forbes's 2005 list, Wegmans ranked 54th.<ref>{{cite journal | magazine=Forbes | title=America's Largest Private Companies | url=https://www.forbes.com/2005/11/09/largest-private-companies_05private_land.html| date=November 11, 2005 | accessdate=November 16, 2006}}</ref>\n\nMost of Wegmans' newer stores are of the [[superstore]] or megamarket type, with a large area, a variety of foods aimed at an upscale [[clientele]], and, in many stores, Market Caf\u00e9 in-store dining areas. From 2002\u20132009, Wegmans owned and operated Tastings, a full-service restaurant at its [[Pittsford (town), New York|Pittsford, New York]] store.<ref name=\"wegmans.com\"/> Tastings was replaced with The Food Bar, a \"seafood shack\"-styled restaurant in the same space; and later with The Burger Bar, serving hamburgers. Next Door by Wegmans, a stand-alone restaurant operated by Wegmans, opened across the street from the Pittsford store in 2009.\n\nIn January 2007, Wegmans announced two business ventures: (1) opening a {{convert|19000|sqft|m2|-2|abbr=on}} liquor store in Pittsford (adding to its two existing wine centers, in Virginia and New Jersey); and (2) the creation of a $28&nbsp;million Culinary Innovation Center in [[Chili, New York]], a corporate research and development facility, including a new central kitchen, replacing some of the operations at its meat center.<ref>{{cite news | last = Rand | first = Ben | title = Wegmans embarks on 2 local projects | work = [[Democrat and Chronicle]]| date = January 6, 2007| url = http://www.democratandchronicle.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20070106/BUSINESS/701060306 | accessdate =January 6, 2007}}{{Dead link|date=January 2010}}</ref> The liquor store opened in April 2008 as Century Pittsford Wines. The store is {{convert|45000|sqft|m2|-2|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pittsfordplaza.com/News/Article.aspx?id=176 |title=Pittsford Plaza \u2013 Century Pittsford Wines run independently of Wegmans |accessdate=June 13, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080616041125/http://www.pittsfordplaza.com/News/Article.aspx?id=176 |archivedate=June 16, 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.allbusiness.com/retail-trade/food-stores/4478555-1.html |title= Rundown of New York State liquor laws prohibiting wine and liquor sales in grocery stores|accessdate=June 13, 2008}}</ref> This business model has been replicated at three other New York Wegmans locations, in Buffalo, DeWitt and Johnson City. Ownership of each liquor store is held by a different member of the Wegman family due to New York State regulations prohibiting individuals or corporations from owning multiple liquor stores.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.buffalonews.com/city-region/north-buffalo-hertel/opening-soon-in-wegmans-parking-lot-amherst-st-wine-liquor-20141017 |title= Opening soon in Wegmans parking lot: Amherst St. Wine & Liquor}}</ref>\n\nAfter Wegmans updated their logo to a script font, in November 2010, [[Walgreens]] filed a [[trademark infringement]] [[lawsuit]] against Wegmans, claiming the \"W\" in the Wegman's logo was too similar to Walgreens.<ref>{{cite news|title=Walgreens sues Wegmans in logo dispute |newspaper=The Wall Street Journal |date=November 6, 2010 |url=http://online.wsj.com/article/AP0d26cbf8d065497781f4dc5f4336a3b3.html |accessdate=November 17, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101108222151/http://online.wsj.com/article/AP0d26cbf8d065497781f4dc5f4336a3b3.html |archivedate=November 8, 2010 }}</ref> The lawsuit was settled in April 2011, with Wegmans agreeing to discontinue use of its \"W\" logo by June 2012, although the supermarket retains the right to use the \"Wegmans\" name in script.<ref name=\"auipb\">{{cite web |url= http://www.ipbrief.net/2011/04/27/wegmans-settles-with-walgreens-over-war-of-w%E2%80%99s/|title= Wegmans Settles with Walgreens over War of W's|author= Richard Patterson|date= April 27, 2011|work= Intellectual Property Brief|publisher= American University|accessdate=June 9, 2011}}</ref> According to Jo Natale, Wegmans director of media relations, \"The cost of making relatively minor changes to a limited number of products was much less than the cost of litigating this case to the end.\"<ref name=\"walgreenpr\">{{cite web|url= http://www.wegmans.com/webapp/wcs/stores/servlet/PressReleaseDetailView?langId=-1&storeId=10052&catalogId=10002&productId=720935|title= Press Release: Wegmans Releases Statement on Lawsuit Resolution|accessdate= June 9, 2011|url-status= dead|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110505055539/http://www.wegmans.com/webapp/wcs/stores/servlet/PressReleaseDetailView?productId=720935&storeId=10052&catalogId=10002&langId=-1|archivedate= May 5, 2011|df= mdy-all}}</ref>\n[[File:Wegmans exterior.jpg|right|200px|thumb|Exterior of a Wegmans store in [[Amherst, New York]], known as the \"Alberta Drive\" location, in 2006, in the style common in the late 1990s]]\nWegmans offers a pick-up service called \"Personal Shopping\" at select locations.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web |url=https://www.wegmans.com/service/personal-shopping.html |title=Personal Shopping |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=2017 |publisher=Wegmans |access-date=January 25, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202074540/https://www.wegmans.com/service/personal-shopping.html |archive-date=February 2, 2017 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> In June 2017, Wegmans partnered with [[Instacart]] to provide home delivery service.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.recode.net/2017/6/14/15793304/wegmans-delivery-instacart-groceries-washington-dc-virginia-maryland |title=The Wegmans grocery chain is introducing delivery in partnership with Instacart |author= Jason Del Rey |date=June 14, 2017 |work=[[Recode]] |access-date=September 19, 2017 |quote=}}</ref>\n\nOn January 30, 2016, Wegmans celebrated its 100th anniversary.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Wegmans celebrates 100 years in business|url = http://www.democratandchronicle.com/story/news/2016/01/30/wegmans-celebrates-100-years-business/79511060/|work = [[Democrat and Chronicle]] |access-date = January 31, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, Wegmans announced its [[Brooklyn]] store would offer grocery delivery to [[Manhattan]] residents, an expansion on their [[Instacart]] partnership. Delivery fees start at $3.99, and Manhattan customers are given a two to five hour delivery window. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://progressivegrocer.com/wegmans-brooklyn-store-offers-grocery-delivery-manhattan|title=Wegmans\u2019 Brooklyn Store Offers Grocery Delivery to Manhattan|website=Progressive Grocer|language=en|access-date=2020-02-19}}</ref>\n\n==Accolades and fanbase==\nWegmans has received much media attention for customer fan base, organic food, [[Salad bar|hot food bar]], the depth of its food selection and employee happiness.<ref>[http://www.pymnts.com/news/retail/2017/the-wonder-of-wegmans-2/ The Wonder Of Wegmans] by PYMNTS.com Posted on January 9, 2017</ref> [[Food Network]] recognized it with its award for Best Grocery Store in 2007.<ref>{{cite press release | title = And the Winner is Wegmans! | publisher = Wegmans | date = April 16, 2007 | url = https://www.wegmans.com/webapp/wcs/stores/servlet/PressReleaseDetailView?langId=-1&storeId=10052&catalogId=10002&productId=399613 | accessdate = October 22, 2008 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110724032925/https://www.wegmans.com/webapp/wcs/stores/servlet/PressReleaseDetailView?langId=-1&storeId=10052&catalogId=10002&productId=399613 | archivedate = July 24, 2011 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> ''[[Consumer Reports]]'' subscribers voted Wegmans the top grocery store in 2017; it has held the top spot since 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.democratandchronicle.com/story/money/business/2017/05/30/consumer-reports-subscribers-again-rank-wegmans-no-1/356210001/|title='Consumer Reports' subscribers pick Wegmans as top grocer, again|publisher=}}</ref> It was also profiled as part of the \"Here Are The Jobs\" segment on [[MSNBC]]'s ''[[PoliticsNation]]'' on July 6, 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/46044226 |title='Here are the jobs' |publisher=NBC News }}</ref> In 2016, Market Force surveyed over 10,000 grocery store shoppers nationwide, and Wegmans was rated \"America's favorite grocery store\".<ref>[http://money.cnn.com/2016/04/20/pf/americas-favorite-grocery-store/  America's favorite grocery store is...] by Kathryn Vasel for CNN; April 20, 2016</ref>\n\nWegmans has a loyal fan base of customers who have received recognition for their devotion, who have lined up overnight in the thousands for a new store opening, regularly write \"[[love letter]]s\" to the store to ask for one to open in a region not presently served, and in [[Northborough, Massachusetts]], many high school students staged a musical about the store.<ref>[http://www.adweek.com/brand-marketing/why-do-so-many-people-go-crazy-wegmans-169396/ Why Do So Many People Go Crazy for Wegmans? \u2013 How an upstate New York grocer found a national cult following] By Robert Klara; February 12, 2016</ref><ref>[https://www.thrillist.com/eat/nation/wegmans-grocery-stores-super-fans HOW WEGMANS INSPIRED THE MOST RABID FANBASE IN THE GROCERY WORLD] By PRIYA KRISHNA for [[Thrillist Media Group]] Published on October 2, 2017</ref> The store's fans have their own Twitter [[hashtag]] \"[https://twitter.com/search?f=tweets&vertical=default&q=wegmania #Wegmania]\" and a Tumblr.\n\n==Chase-Pitkin Home and Garden Centers==\nWegmans was the parent company of Chase-Pitkin, a regional [[home improvement]] retailer. On October 4, 2005, Wegmans announced that it would close all Chase-Pitkin stores by early 2006<ref name=\"aubpub\">{{cite web |url=http://www.auburnpub.com/news/local/article_a80b2670-7696-52bf-8f1b-c30970206dcd.html?mode=story|title= Wegmans to close all Chase-Pitkins |date= October 5, 2005|publisher= auburnpub.com|accessdate=January 4, 2010}}</ref> and focus on its supermarket operations. The decision to exit the home improvement business was reportedly due to the increasing dominance of national chains such as [[Lowe's]] and [[The Home Depot]].<ref name=\"aubpub\"/> Chase-Pitkin stores closed individually at various points throughout March 2006.{{citation needed|date=November 2017}}\n\n==Discontinuation of tobacco products==\nIn January 2008, Wegmans announced that it would no longer sell tobacco products because of their negative effects on human health and the environment<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/baltimore/stories/2007/12/31/daily30.html|title=Wegmans ceasing tobacco sales|publisher=Baltimore Business Journal|author=James Fink|date=January 4, 2008|accessdate=January 4, 2010}}</ref> and would offer smoking cessation programs to all employees.<ref name=\"conaff1\">{{cite web|title=Wegmans, DeCicco Markets Ditch Cigarettes|url=http://www.consumeraffairs.com/news04/2008/06/stores_tobacco.html|publisher=consumeraffairs.com|date=June 2, 2008|accessdate=January 4, 2010}}</ref> The decision drew praise from the [[American Lung Association]] of New York State, which presented Wegmans with the \"Lung Champion Award\".<ref name=\"conaff1\"/>\n\n==Wegmans brand==\nWegmans began branding some products in 1979, offering basic commodities at a lower price than national brands. The Wegmans brand has gradually expanded. In 1992, it began a line of healthy products, Food You Feel Good About. Wegmans brand products marked with the Food You Feel Good About banner indicate that the product does not contain artificial colors, flavors, or preservatives. The next sub-brand to be launched was Italian Classics, in 1995; it introduced pastas, canned tomatoes, and olive oils imported from Italy. In 2002, Wegmans launched a line of organic products. Organic Wegmans brand products are labeled with a green leaf.\n\n==In popular culture==\nThe Wegmans brand was used extensively in the American sitcom ''[[The Office (U.S. TV series)|The Office]]''. The program is set in the city of [[Scranton, Pennsylvania]], which has a Wegmans store, although the series was filmed in suburban Los Angeles.<ref>{{cite news | first = Christine Carrie | last = Fien | title =  TV SCENE: Wegmans checks in at 'The Office' | url = http://www.rochestercitynewspaper.com/news/articles/TV+SCENE:+Wegmans+checks+in+at++The+Office+/ | work = [[City Newspaper]] | date = March 7, 2007 | accessdate =April 12, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.wegmans.com/webapp/wcs/stores/servlet/StoreDetailView?langId=-1&storeId=10052&catalogId=10002&productId=347976 | title = Wegmans Locator Detail for Scranton, PA | publisher = Wegmans | accessdate = April 12, 2008 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080612201458/http://www.wegmans.com/webapp/wcs/stores/servlet/StoreDetailView?langId=-1&storeId=10052&catalogId=10002&productId=347976 | archivedate = June 12, 2008 | df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nWegman's Bake and Rise Four Cheese Frozen Pizza has been reviewed on Barstool Sports' One Bite Pizza Reviews by David Portnoy. The score for the frozen pizza was an 8.1. Per, Portnoy this score is on the frozen pizza scale and does not translate to an 8.1 on the normal pizza place scale score. However, as of April 9th, 2020, this is the highest score Portnoy has given to a frozen pizza.<ref>https://www.barstoolsports.com/video/2257799/barstool-frozen-pizza-review-wegmans-pizza</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* ''Wegmans footprint in Pennsylvania'' ~ {{cite news | url=http://www.bizjournals.com/philadelphia/blog/real-estate/2014/07/wegmans-leases-land-in-chadds-ford-plans-140-000.html | title=Wegmans leases land in Chadds Ford, plans 140,000-square-foot store | work=[[Phila. Bus. J.]] | date=July 25, 2014 | author=Kostelni, Natalie }}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|New York (state)|Companies|Food}}\n* {{official website|https://www.wegmans.com/}}\n\n{{Supermarkets of the United States}}\n{{City of Rochester, NY}}\n\n[[Category:Economy of the Northeastern United States]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Rochester, New York]]\n[[Category:Privately held companies based in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Retail companies established in 1916]]\n[[Category:Supermarkets of the United States]]\n[[Category:1916 establishments in New York (state)]]\n", "name_user": "AndrewT2020", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eOperations", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wegmans"}
{"title_page": "David McReynolds", "text_new": "{{short description|American politician and social activist}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2014}}\n{{Infobox politician\n| name                = David McReynolds\n| image               = NLN David McReynolds.jpg\n| caption             = McReynolds at the 2009 Left Forum in [[New York City]]\n| party               = Independent\n| otherparty          = [[Socialist Party USA|Socialist Party]] (1951\u20132015)<br>[[Prohibition Party]] (before 1951)<ref name=\"thevillager.com\">Mulkerin, Joseph. [http://thevillager.com/2015/08/27/a-socialist-presidential-candidate-no-not-that-one-looks-back/ \"A socialist presidential candidate \u2014 no, not that one \u2014 looks back\"]. ''[[The Villager (Manhattan)|The Villager]]'', 27 August 2015. Retrieved 28 August 2015.</ref><br> [[Green Party (United States)|Green]] (affiliated non-member)\n|birth_name=David Ernest McReynolds<ref>James T. Havel. [https://books.google.ca/books?id=BwgWAQAAIAAJ&q=%22David+Ernest+McReynolds%22&dq=%22David+Ernest+McReynolds%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwitqY3vg_bcAhXp7IMKHWxQCJ4Q6AEIFDAA ''The Elections, 1789-1992''], Macmillan Library Reference USA, (1996)</ref>\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date|1929|10|25}}\n| birth_place         = [[Los Angeles, California]]\n| alma_mater          = [[University of California Los Angeles]]\n| death_date          = {{death date and age|2018|8|17|1929|10|25}}\n| death_place         = [[New York, New York]]\n| religion            = \n| occupation          = Activist, politician, writer\n}}\n{{Commonscat}}\n'''David Ernest McReynolds''' (October 25, 1929 \u2013 August 17, 2018) was an American politician and [[social activist]] who was a prominent [[democratic socialism|democratic socialist]] and [[pacifist]] [[activist]]. He described himself as \"a peace movement bureaucrat\" during his 40-year career with the [[War Resisters League]].<ref>David McReynolds, \"Thinking About Retirement\", ''Nonviolent Activist'', March\u2013April 1999, p. 7.</ref><ref name=DubermanSavingRemnant>[https://www.amazon.com/Saving-Remnant-Radical-Barbara-McReynolds/dp/1595583238 Martin Duberman, ''A Saving Remnant: The Radical Lives of Barbara Deming and David McReynolds,'' New York: The New Press (2011)]{{rp|221}}</ref> He was a resident of New York City.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/CandidateDetail.html?CandidateID=7993|title=Our Campaigns - Candidate - David McReynolds|website=www.ourcampaigns.com|accessdate=October 4, 2017}}</ref> McReynolds was twice a candidate for [[President of the United States]], running atop the ticket of the [[Socialist Party USA]] in 1980 and 2000. He was America's first openly gay presidential candidate.<ref>https://www.thevillager.com/2018/08/david-mcreynolds-pacifist-and-socialist-leader-is-dead-at-88/</ref>\n\n{{American socialism |expanded=People}}\n\n==Early life==\nMcReynolds was born in Los Angeles, to Elizabeth Grace (Tallon), a nurse, and Lt. Col. Charles McReynolds, an Air Force intelligence officer.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ourcampaigns.com/CandidateDetail.html?CandidateID=7993 |title=Candidate - David McReynolds |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2019-05-30}}</ref> In 1951 he joined the [[Socialist Party of America]] (SPA) and in 1953 he graduated from [[UCLA]] with a degree in [[political science]]. Between 1957 and 1960, he worked for the [[editorial board]] of the left-wing magazine ''[[Liberation (magazine)|Liberation]]''. He was [[openly gay]] and wrote his first article about living as a gay man in 1969.<ref>Leaders from the 1960s: A Biographical Sourcebook of American Activism. Edited By David De Leon Published by Greenwood Publishing Group, 1994 {{ISBN|0-313-27414-2}} pp.215\u2013219</ref>\n\n==War Resisters League==\nMcReynolds was staunchly [[anti-war]] and a [[Conscription#Draft resisters|draft resister]], and in 1960 joined the staff of the [[War Resisters League]] (WRL), where he remained until his retirement in 1999. In 1965 he lectured on \"The Old Left and the New Left\" at the newly founded [[Free University of New York]].<ref>{{Citation| last = [[Joseph Berke|Berke]]| first = Joseph\n| title = The Free University of New York| journal = Peace News| volume =| issue =|date=October 29, 1965| pages = 6\u20137| url =}} as reproduced in {{Citation\n |last=Jakobsen \n |first=Jakob \n |title=Anti-University of Londin\u2013Antihistory Tabloid \n |publisher=MayDay Rooms \n |location=London \n |year=2012 \n |pages=6\u20137 \n |url=http://maydayrooms.org/room-3-research/ \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121012141942/http://maydayrooms.org/room-3-research/ \n |archivedate=October 12, 2012 \n |df=mdy \n}}</ref>\n\nOn November 6, 1965, he was one of five men who publicly [[Draft-card burning|burned their draft cards]] at an [[Opposition to the Vietnam War#The draft|anti-war demonstration]] at Union Square in New York.  This was one of the first public draft-card burnings after U.S. law was changed on August 30, 1965 to make such actions a felony, punishable by up to five years' imprisonment. He was close friends with [[Bayard Rustin]]<ref>John D'Emilio. READING THE SILENCES IN A GAY LIFE The Case of Bayard Rustin pp. 59\u201368 in The Seductions of Biography. Edited: Mary Rhiel, David Suchoff, David Bruce Suchoff. Routledge, 1996 {{ISBN|0-415-91089-7}}<br>\n\"Rustin's only defender was Dave McReynolds, a younger gay staffer at the War Resisters League, whom Rustin had mentored over the years\"</ref> and other prominent peace activists, as well as literary figures such as [[Quentin Crisp]].<ref>Dave McReynolds. [http://www.crisperanto.org/memories/mcreynolds.html NOTES ON KNOWING QUENTIN]. and [http://www.crisperanto.org/memories/mcreynolds1.html QUENTIN CRISP: THE RADICAL], Quentin Crisp Archives (2005)</ref>\n\nIn 1968, he signed the \"[[Writers and Editors War Tax Protest]]\" pledge, vowing to refuse tax payments in protest against the Vietnam War,<ref>\"Writers and Editors War Tax Protest\" January 30, 1968 ''New York Post''</ref> and later became a sponsor of the War Tax Resistance project, which practiced and advocated [[tax resistance]] as a form of anti-war protest.<ref>\"A Call to War Tax Resistance\" ''The Cycle'' 14 May 1970, p.&nbsp;7</ref>\n\nMcReynolds was particularly active internationally, both in [[War Resisters' International]], of which he was chairperson for the term 1986\u201388, and in the International Confederation for Disarmament and Peace, which eventually merged into the [[International Peace Bureau]].\n\n==Socialist Party USA==\nThe SPA was renamed the [[Social Democrats USA]] by a majority vote at the 1972 convention. [[Michael Harrington]] resigned and then formed the [[Democratic Socialist Organizing Committee]] (now the [[Democratic Socialists of America]], DSA) with the purpose of \"realignment\" strengthening the role of labor unions and other progressive organizations in the [[United States Democratic Party|Democratic Party]] to pull it to the left.  The smallest and the most left wing faction of the SPA, known as the [[Debs Caucus]], including McReynolds, formed the [[Socialist Party USA]] (SPUSA).  McReynolds was long a member of both DSA and SPUSA.\n\nMcReynolds' primary theoretical contribution to socialism came from his blending of a [[pacifist]] world-view with a commitment to re-distributive [[socialist economics]].  Politically, he was a staunch [[anti-authoritarian]] and collaborated with a diverse set of political formations on the democratic left.  His widely read pamphlet, ''The Philosophy of Nonviolence'', provides a unique window into the mind of a lifelong activist wrestling with the contradictions and pitfalls which plagued the political left in the 20th century.  He concludes that \"...there is no living, vital philosophy which does not have 'holes' in it.\"  Consequently, he mapped out a [[Pluralism (philosophy)|pluralistic]] approach which is, on the one hand, socialist, yet is entirely engaged with thought systems as seemingly contradictory as [[Hindu philosophy]].  He concluded that a brand of pacifist-socialism is best suited for future socialist experiments since it offers the greatest opportunity to prefigure the kinds of democratic relations necessary to create a functional and free society.{{Clarify|date=September 2010}}\n\nIn his political career, McReynolds ran for [[United States Congress|Congress]] from [[Lower Manhattan]] twice and for [[President of the United States|President]] twice.  In 1958 he ran as a write-in SPA candidate and then in 1968 as a [[Peace and Freedom Party]] candidate for Congress in the 19th district pulling in 4.7% of the vote (3,969 votes).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://clerk.house.gov/member_info/electionInfo/1968election.pdf |title=Statistics of the Presidential and Congressional Election of November 5, 1968 |publisher= |date= |accessdate=2011-09-27}}</ref> In 1980, he ran for President of the United States as the SPUSA candidate, with [[Diane Drufenbrock]] as vice presidential candidate, receiving 6,994 votes (0.01%).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uselectionatlas.org/RESULTS/national.php?year=1980&off=0 |title=1980 Presidential General Election Results |publisher= |date= |accessdate=2011-09-27}}</ref><ref>Kari Lydersen. David vs. Goliath. In These Times. Vol. 24, No. 10 (2000). <br>\nOn his 1980 presidential run:\n\"He was among the first openly gay political candidates for any office, having come out in WIN magazine in 1969, and though he doesn't see himself as a \"gay and lesbian candidate,\" he has continued to work for gay rights.\"</ref>  He ran again for president as the SPUSA candidate in 2000 with [[Mary Cal Hollis]] as his running mate, receiving 5,602 votes.  In both 1980 and 2000, McReynolds received the endorsement and ballot line of the [[Liberty Union Party]] in Vermont.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thegreenpapers.com/G00/VT.html#Pre |title=Vermont November 2000 General Election |publisher=Thegreenpapers.com |date= |accessdate=2011-09-27}}</ref>\n[[File:Butterfly Ballot, Florida 2000 (large).jpg|thumb|360px|Palm Beach County's \"butterfly ballot\"]]\nAfter the 2000 election the ''Palm Beach Post'' speculated that the vast majority of the 2,908 voters who had voided their votes by punching the names of both McReynolds and Democratic candidate Al Gore on a \"confusing [[butterfly ballot]]\" (and also of the over 3,000 more who punched both Gore and Buchanan) had meant to vote for Gore and that mistaken voting on the Palm Beach County butterfly ballot had consequently cost Gore the state's crucial electoral votes, and therefore the election as a whole.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.palmbeachpost.com/politics/content/news/election2000/election2000_overvote_gore.html |title=Joel Engelhardt and Scott McCabe, \"Over-votes cost Gore the election in Florida,\" '&#39;Palm Beach Post,'&#39; undated website |publisher=Palmbeachpost.com |accessdate=2011-09-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110616195335/http://www.palmbeachpost.com/politics/content/news/election2000/election2000_overvote_gore.html |archivedate=June 16, 2011 |df=mdy-all }} </ref>\n\nIn January 2015, the [[Socialist Party USA]]'s National Committee voted to [[censure]] McReynolds over alleged racist comments made on social media regarding the [[Charlie Hebdo shooting]] and [[shooting of Michael Brown]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Reinholz|first=Mary|title=Rift Among Socialists Over Former Presidential Hopeful\u2019s \u2018Potentially Racist\u2019 Comments About Michael Brown|url=http://bedfordandbowery.com/2015/05/rift-among-socialists-over-former-presidential-hopefuls-potentially-racist-comments-about-michael-brown/|publisher=Bedford + Bowery|date=May 1, 2015|accessdate=February 16, 2016}}</ref> He resigned from the SPUSA shortly thereafter.<ref name=\"thevillager.com\"/>\n\n==2004 Senate campaign==\n{{Main|United States Senate election in New York, 2004}}\nOn July 10, 2004, McReynolds announced his candidacy running on the [[Green Party (United States)|Green Party]] ticket for one of the New York seats in the [[United States Senate elections, 2004|Senate]], running an anti-war campaign against Democratic incumbent [[Chuck Schumer]], where he pulled in 36,942 votes for 0.5% of total.<ref name=DubermanSavingRemnant/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elections.ny.gov/NYSBOE/elections/2006/general/2006_ussen.pdf |title=NYS Board of Elections US Senate Election Returns Nov. 7, 2006 |format=PDF |accessdate=2011-09-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120822221220/http://www.elections.ny.gov/NYSBOE/elections/2006/general/2006_ussen.pdf |archivedate=August 22, 2012 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\n==Later life==\nMcReynolds was active politically until just before his death, attending meetings, speaking in classrooms, being interviewed for films and research, and participating in peace, justice, antiwar, and antinuclear actions. His last arrest was at the U.S. Mission to the United Nations in 2015 at an action calling for immediate nuclear disarmament. \n\nHe was an avid photographer throughout his adult life and spent time during the last three years of his life sorting his collection of more than 50,000 photos.\n\nIn 2015, McReynolds endorsed U.S. Senator [[Bernie Sanders]] for [[President of the United States]], praising him as a \"serious candidate\" and for not personally attacking his Democratic rival [[Hillary Clinton]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.peoplesworld.org/article/why-i-support-bernie-sanders/|title=Why I support Bernie Sanders|publisher=Peoples World|date=July 7, 2015}}</ref>\n\nMcReynolds died on August 17, 2018, aged 88, following a fall he sustained at his New York City home.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/ny-news-david-mcreynolds-dead-88-story.html|title=David McReynolds, longtime peace activist and agitator, dead at 88|publisher=New York Daily News|date=August 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== Works ==\n* ''We Have Been Invaded by the 21st Century.'' Praeger, 1970.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100701044409/http://www.warresisters.org/nva/nva0399-3.htm \"Thinking About Retirement,\"] ''Nonviolent Activist'', March\u2013April 1999.\n* [http://newpol.org/content/queer-reflections \"Queer Reflections,\"] ''[[New Politics (magazine)|New Politics]]'', Vol 12, no. 1 (2008).\n* [http://www.mcreynoldsphotos.org/ \"David McReynolds Photography\"]\n\n==Further reading==\n* [[Paul Buhle]], [https://web.archive.org/web/20081026220247/http://www.warresisters.org/nva/nva0399-2.htm \"David McReynolds:Socialist Peacemaker\"]. ''Nonviolent Activist'', March\u2013April 1999.\n* Scott H. Bennett, \"Conscience, Comrades, and the Cold War: The Korean War Draft Resistance Cases of Socialist Pacifists David McReynolds and Vern Davidson,\" ''Peace and Change,'' vol. 38, no. 1 (Jan. 2013), pp.&nbsp;83\u2013120.\n* Scott H. Bennett, ''Radical Pacifism: The War Resisters League and Gandhian Nonviolence in America, 1915\u20131963.'' Syracuse University Press, 2003.\n* [[Dan Vera]], \"Being Peaceful: An Interview with David McReynolds.\" ''[[White Crane (magazine)|White Crane]],'' No. 57 (Summer 2003), pp.&nbsp;4\u201310.\n* Keith Stern, ''Queers in History.'' Dallas, Texas: BenBella Books, 2009.\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20040701084622/http://www.sp-usa.org/ Socialist Party USA]\n* [http://www.warresisters.org War Resisters League]\n* [http://cyberspacei.com/jesusi/peace/non_resistance/dm/ ''The Philosophy of Nonviolence''] by David McReynolds\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20041222091744/http://www.thesocialistparty.org/spo/archive/McR/index.html ''The Infinite Series''] by David McReynolds\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060502130736/http://www.mytown.ca/mcreynolds/ His articles at MyTown]\n* Paul Buhle, [https://web.archive.org/web/20071016121956/http://www.warresisters.org/nva0399-2.htm ''David McReynolds: Socia