a]]\n[[Category:Members of the Socialist Party of America]]\n[[Category:Socialist Party USA politicians from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Socialist Party USA presidential nominees]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 1980 United States presidential election]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 2000 United States presidential election]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 2004 United States elections]]\n[[Category:20th-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:Politicians from New York City]]\n[[Category:Gay politicians]]\n[[Category:LGBT politicians from the United States]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from California]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:American atheists]]\n[[Category:Marxist humanists]]\n[[Category:University of California, Los Angeles alumni]]\n[[Category:Accidental deaths in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Deaths from falls]]\n[[Category:1929 births]]\n[[Category:2018 deaths]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American politician and social activist}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2014}}\n{{Infobox politician\n| name                = David McReynolds\n| image               = NLN David McReynolds.jpg\n| caption             = McReynolds at the 2009 Left Forum in [[New York City]]\n| party               = Independent\n| otherparty          = [[Socialist Party USA|Socialist Party]] (1951\u20132015)<br>[[Prohibition Party]] (before 1951)<ref name=\"thevillager.com\">Mulkerin, Joseph. [http://thevillager.com/2015/08/27/a-socialist-presidential-candidate-no-not-that-one-looks-back/ \"A socialist presidential candidate \u2014 no, not that one \u2014 looks back\"]. ''[[The Villager (Manhattan)|The Villager]]'', 27 August 2015. Retrieved 28 August 2015.</ref><br> [[Green Party (United States)|Green]] (affiliated non-member)\n|birth_name=David Ernest McReynolds<ref>James T. Havel. [https://books.google.ca/books?id=BwgWAQAAIAAJ&q=%22David+Ernest+McReynolds%22&dq=%22David+Ernest+McReynolds%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwitqY3vg_bcAhXp7IMKHWxQCJ4Q6AEIFDAA ''The Elections, 1789-1992''], Macmillan Library Reference USA, (1996)</ref>\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date|1929|10|25}}\n| birth_place         = [[Los Angeles, California]]\n| alma_mater          = [[University of California Los Angeles]]\n| death_date          = {{death date and age|2018|8|17|1929|10|25}}\n| death_place         = [[New York, New York]]\n| religion            = \n| occupation          = Activist, politician, writer\n}}\n{{Commonscat}}\n'''David Ernest McReynolds''' (October 25, 1929 \u2013 August 17, 2018) was an American politician and [[social activist]] who was a prominent [[democratic socialism|democratic socialist]] and [[pacifist]] [[activist]]. He described himself as \"a peace movement bureaucrat\" during his 40-year career with the [[War Resisters League]].<ref>David McReynolds, \"Thinking About Retirement\", ''Nonviolent Activist'', March\u2013April 1999, p. 7.</ref><ref name=DubermanSavingRemnant>[https://www.amazon.com/Saving-Remnant-Radical-Barbara-McReynolds/dp/1595583238 Martin Duberman, ''A Saving Remnant: The Radical Lives of Barbara Deming and David McReynolds,'' New York: The New Press (2011)]{{rp|221}}</ref> He was a resident of New York City.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/CandidateDetail.html?CandidateID=7993|title=Our Campaigns - Candidate - David McReynolds|website=www.ourcampaigns.com|accessdate=October 4, 2017}}</ref> McReynolds was twice a candidate for [[President of the United States]], running atop the ticket of the [[Socialist Party USA]] in 1980 and 2000. He was America's first openly gay presidential candidate.<ref>https://www.thevillager.com/2018/08/david-mcreynolds-pacifist-and-socialist-leader-is-dead-at-88/</ref>\n\n{{American socialism |expanded=People}}\n\n==Early life==\nMcReynolds was born in Los Angeles, to Elizabeth Grace (Tallon), a nurse, and Lt. Col. Charles McReynolds, an Air Force intelligence officer.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ourcampaigns.com/CandidateDetail.html?CandidateID=7993 |title=Candidate - David McReynolds |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2019-05-30}}</ref> In 1951 he joined the [[Socialist Party of America]] (SPA) and in 1953 he graduated from [[UCLA]] with a degree in [[political science]]. Between 1957 and 1960, he worked for the [[editorial board]] of the left-wing magazine ''[[Liberation (magazine)|Liberation]]''. He was [[openly gay]] and wrote his first article about living as a gay man in 1969.<ref>Leaders from the 1960s: A Biographical Sourcebook of American Activism. Edited By David De Leon Published by Greenwood Publishing Group, 1994 {{ISBN|0-313-27414-2}} pp.215\u2013219</ref>\n\n==War Resisters League==\nMcReynolds was staunchly [[anti-war]] and a [[Conscription#Draft resisters|draft resister]], and in 1960 joined the staff of the [[War Resisters League]] (WRL), where he remained until his retirement in 1999. In 1965 he lectured on \"The Old Left and the New Left\" at the newly founded [[Free University of New York]].<ref>{{Citation| last = [[Joseph Berke|Berke]]| first = Joseph\n| title = The Free University of New York| journal = Peace News| volume =| issue =|date=October 29, 1965| pages = 6\u20137| url =}} as reproduced in {{Citation\n |last=Jakobsen \n |first=Jakob \n |title=Anti-University of Londin\u2013Antihistory Tabloid \n |publisher=MayDay Rooms \n |location=London \n |year=2012 \n |pages=6\u20137 \n |url=http://maydayrooms.org/room-3-research/ \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121012141942/http://maydayrooms.org/room-3-research/ \n |archivedate=October 12, 2012 \n |df=mdy \n}}</ref>\n\nOn November 6, 1965, he was one of five men who publicly [[Draft-card burning|burned their draft cards]] at an [[Opposition to the Vietnam War#The draft|anti-war demonstration]] at Union Square in New York.  This was one of the first public draft-card burnings after U.S. law was changed on August 30, 1965 to make such actions a felony, punishable by up to five years' imprisonment. He was close friends with [[Bayard Rustin]]<ref>John D'Emilio. READING THE SILENCES IN A GAY LIFE The Case of Bayard Rustin pp. 59\u201368 in The Seductions of Biography. Edited: Mary Rhiel, David Suchoff, David Bruce Suchoff. Routledge, 1996 {{ISBN|0-415-91089-7}}<br>\n\"Rustin's only defender was Dave McReynolds, a younger gay staffer at the War Resisters League, whom Rustin had mentored over the years\"</ref> and other prominent peace activists, as well as literary figures such as [[Quentin Crisp]].<ref>Dave McReynolds. [http://www.crisperanto.org/memories/mcreynolds.html NOTES ON KNOWING QUENTIN]. and [http://www.crisperanto.org/memories/mcreynolds1.html QUENTIN CRISP: THE RADICAL], Quentin Crisp Archives (2005)</ref>\n\nIn 1968, he signed the \"[[Writers and Editors War Tax Protest]]\" pledge, vowing to refuse tax payments in protest against the Vietnam War,<ref>\"Writers and Editors War Tax Protest\" January 30, 1968 ''New York Post''</ref> and later became a sponsor of the War Tax Resistance project, which practiced and advocated [[tax resistance]] as a form of anti-war protest.<ref>\"A Call to War Tax Resistance\" ''The Cycle'' 14 May 1970, p.&nbsp;7</ref>\n\nMcReynolds was particularly active internationally, both in [[War Resisters' International]], of which he was chairperson for the term 1986\u201388, and in the International Confederation for Disarmament and Peace, which eventually merged into the [[International Peace Bureau]].\n\n==Socialist Party USA==\nThe SPA was renamed the [[Social Democrats USA]] by a majority vote at the 1972 convention. [[Michael Harrington]] resigned and then formed the [[Democratic Socialist Organizing Committee]] (now the [[Democratic Socialists of America]], DSA) with the purpose of \"realignment\" strengthening the role of labor unions and other progressive organizations in the [[United States Democratic Party|Democratic Party]] to pull it to the left.  The smallest and the most left wing faction of the SPA, known as the [[Debs Caucus]], including McReynolds, formed the [[Socialist Party USA]] (SPUSA).  McReynolds was long a member of both DSA and SPUSA.\n\nMcReynolds' primary theoretical contribution to socialism came from his blending of a [[pacifist]] world-view with a commitment to re-distributive [[socialist economics]].  Politically, he was a staunch [[anti-authoritarian]] and collaborated with a diverse set of political formations on the democratic left.  His widely read pamphlet, ''The Philosophy of Nonviolence'', provides a unique window into the mind of a lifelong activist wrestling with the contradictions and pitfalls which plagued the political left in the 20th century.  He concludes that \"...there is no living, vital philosophy which does not have 'holes' in it.\"  Consequently, he mapped out a [[Pluralism (philosophy)|pluralistic]] approach which is, on the one hand, socialist, yet is entirely engaged with thought systems as seemingly contradictory as [[Hindu philosophy]].  He concluded that a brand of pacifist-socialism is best suited for future socialist experiments since it offers the greatest opportunity to prefigure the kinds of democratic relations necessary to create a functional and free society.{{Clarify|date=September 2010}}\n\nIn his political career, McReynolds ran for [[United States Congress|Congress]] from [[Lower Manhattan]] twice and for [[President of the United States|President]] twice.  In 1958 he ran as a write-in SPA candidate and then in 1968 as a [[Peace and Freedom Party]] candidate for Congress in the 19th district pulling in 4.7% of the vote (3,969 votes).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://clerk.house.gov/member_info/electionInfo/1968election.pdf |title=Statistics of the Presidential and Congressional Election of November 5, 1968 |publisher= |date= |accessdate=2011-09-27}}</ref> In 1980, he ran for President of the United States as the SPUSA candidate, with [[Diane Drufenbrock]] as vice presidential candidate, receiving 6,994 votes (0.01%).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uselectionatlas.org/RESULTS/national.php?year=1980&off=0 |title=1980 Presidential General Election Results |publisher= |date= |accessdate=2011-09-27}}</ref><ref>Kari Lydersen. David vs. Goliath. In These Times. Vol. 24, No. 10 (2000). <br>\nOn his 1980 presidential run:\n\"He was among the first openly gay political candidates for any office, having come out in WIN magazine in 1969, and though he doesn't see himself as a \"gay and lesbian candidate,\" he has continued to work for gay rights.\"</ref>  He ran again for President as the SPUSA candidate in 2000 with [[Mary Cal Hollis]] as his running mate, receiving 5,602 votes.  In both 1980 and 2000, McReynolds received the endorsement and ballot line of the [[Liberty Union Party]] in Vermont.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thegreenpapers.com/G00/VT.html#Pre |title=Vermont November 2000 General Election |publisher=Thegreenpapers.com |date= |accessdate=2011-09-27}}</ref>\n[[File:Butterfly Ballot, Florida 2000 (large).jpg|thumb|360px|Palm Beach County's \"butterfly ballot\"]]\nAfter the 2000 election the ''Palm Beach Post'' speculated that the vast majority of the 2,908 voters who had voided their votes by punching the names of both McReynolds and Democratic candidate Al Gore on a \"confusing [[butterfly ballot]]\" (and also of the over 3,000 more who punched both Gore and Buchanan) had meant to vote for Gore and that mistaken voting on the Palm Beach County butterfly ballot had consequently cost Gore the state's crucial electoral votes, and therefore the election as a whole.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.palmbeachpost.com/politics/content/news/election2000/election2000_overvote_gore.html |title=Joel Engelhardt and Scott McCabe, \"Over-votes cost Gore the election in Florida,\" '&#39;Palm Beach Post,'&#39; undated website |publisher=Palmbeachpost.com |accessdate=2011-09-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110616195335/http://www.palmbeachpost.com/politics/content/news/election2000/election2000_overvote_gore.html |archivedate=June 16, 2011 |df=mdy-all }} </ref>\n\nIn January 2015, the [[Socialist Party USA]]'s National Committee voted to [[censure]] McReynolds over alleged racist comments made on social media regarding the [[Charlie Hebdo shooting]] and [[shooting of Michael Brown]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Reinholz|first=Mary|title=Rift Among Socialists Over Former Presidential Hopeful\u2019s \u2018Potentially Racist\u2019 Comments About Michael Brown|url=http://bedfordandbowery.com/2015/05/rift-among-socialists-over-former-presidential-hopefuls-potentially-racist-comments-about-michael-brown/|publisher=Bedford + Bowery|date=May 1, 2015|accessdate=February 16, 2016}}</ref> He resigned from the SPUSA shortly thereafter.<ref name=\"thevillager.com\"/>\n\n==2004 Senate campaign==\n{{Main|United States Senate election in New York, 2004}}\nOn July 10, 2004, McReynolds announced his candidacy running on the [[Green Party (United States)|Green Party]] ticket for one of the New York seats in the [[United States Senate elections, 2004|Senate]], running an anti-war campaign against Democratic incumbent [[Chuck Schumer]], where he pulled in 36,942 votes for 0.5% of total.<ref name=DubermanSavingRemnant/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elections.ny.gov/NYSBOE/elections/2006/general/2006_ussen.pdf |title=NYS Board of Elections US Senate Election Returns Nov. 7, 2006 |format=PDF |accessdate=2011-09-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120822221220/http://www.elections.ny.gov/NYSBOE/elections/2006/general/2006_ussen.pdf |archivedate=August 22, 2012 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\n==Later life==\nMcReynolds was active politically until just before his death, attending meetings, speaking in classrooms, being interviewed for films and research, and participating in peace, justice, antiwar, and antinuclear actions. His last arrest was at the U.S. Mission to the United Nations in 2015 at an action calling for immediate nuclear disarmament. \n\nHe was an avid photographer throughout his adult life and spent time during the last three years of his life sorting his collection of more than 50,000 photos.\n\nIn 2015, McReynolds endorsed U.S. Senator [[Bernie Sanders]] for [[President of the United States]], praising him as a \"serious candidate\" and for not personally attacking his Democratic rival [[Hillary Clinton]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.peoplesworld.org/article/why-i-support-bernie-sanders/|title=Why I support Bernie Sanders|publisher=Peoples World|date=July 7, 2015}}</ref>\n\nMcReynolds died on August 17, 2018, aged 88, following a fall he sustained at his New York City home.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/ny-news-david-mcreynolds-dead-88-story.html|title=David McReynolds, longtime peace activist and agitator, dead at 88|publisher=New York Daily News|date=August 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== Works ==\n* ''We Have Been Invaded by the 21st Century.'' Praeger, 1970.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100701044409/http://www.warresisters.org/nva/nva0399-3.htm \"Thinking About Retirement,\"] ''Nonviolent Activist'', March\u2013April 1999.\n* [http://newpol.org/content/queer-reflections \"Queer Reflections,\"] ''[[New Politics (magazine)|New Politics]]'', Vol 12, no. 1 (2008).\n* [http://www.mcreynoldsphotos.org/ \"David McReynolds Photography\"]\n\n==Further reading==\n* [[Paul Buhle]], [https://web.archive.org/web/20081026220247/http://www.warresisters.org/nva/nva0399-2.htm \"David McReynolds:Socialist Peacemaker\"]. ''Nonviolent Activist'', March\u2013April 1999.\n* Scott H. Bennett, \"Conscience, Comrades, and the Cold War: The Korean War Draft Resistance Cases of Socialist Pacifists David McReynolds and Vern Davidson,\" ''Peace and Change,'' vol. 38, no. 1 (Jan. 2013), pp.&nbsp;83\u2013120.\n* Scott H. Bennett, ''Radical Pacifism: The War Resisters League and Gandhian Nonviolence in America, 1915\u20131963.'' Syracuse University Press, 2003.\n* [[Dan Ver